{"title_page": "Samira Kiani", "text_new": "{{short description|Health systems engineer}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Samira Kiani\n| alma_mater = [[Tehran University of Medical Sciences]] <br>\n| workplaces = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] <br> [[Arizona State University]]\n| known_for = [[CRISPR]]\n}}\n\n'''Samira Kiani''' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0627 \u06a9\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}) is an Associate Professor in the department of Pathology of [[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine]] and Pittsburgh Liver Research Center. Formerly, she was a Health Systems Engineer at [[Arizona State University]]. Her work combines [[Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeat]] ([[CRISPR]]) with synthetic biology. She is a 2019 [[American Association for the Advancement of Science|AAAS]] Leshner Fellow.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKiani is from [[Iran]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://innercircle.engineering.asu.edu/2016/03/01/meet-your-new-sbhse-faculty/|title=Meet your new SBHSE faculty {{!}} Inner Circle|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She earned her medical degree at the [[Tehran University of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://theinnovationinstitute.org/samira-kiani|title=Samira Kiani|website=TheInnovationInstitute.Org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She completed a thesis on the molecular mechanisms of tissue injury.<ref name=\":1\" /> She joined the [[Freeman Hospital]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], where she was trained in general medicine.<ref name=\":1\" /> She joined the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], working as a postdoctoral researcher in [[Synthetic biology|synthetic biology]] at MIT Synthetic Biology Center.<ref name=\":1\" /> She has acted as an advisor for the [[MIT]] International Genetically Engineered Machine (iGEM) team.<ref name=\":1\" /> She collaborated with George Church and Ron Weiss to advance [[CRISPR]] technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiche.org/community/bio/samira-kiani|title=Samira Kiani|date=2017-10-19|website=www.aiche.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Weiss|first=Ron|last2=Li|first2=Yinqing|last3=Xie|first3=Zhen|last4=Richard N. Hall|last5=Huh|first5=Jin|last6=Ebrahimkhani|first6=Mohammad R.|last7=Beal|first7=Jacob|last8=Kiani|first8=Samira|date=2014|title=CRISPR transcriptional repression devices and layered circuits in mammalian cells|journal=Nature Methods|language=en|volume=11|issue=7|pages=723\u2013726|doi=10.1038/nmeth.2969|pmid=24797424|issn=1548-7105|pmc=4228775}}</ref> They developed a [[CRISPR]] based a modular transcriptional repression architecture that can be used to create functional cascaded circuits.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Research and career ==\nKiani joined [[Arizona State University]] in 2016 and later moved to University of Pittsburgh in January 2020.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isearch.asu.edu/profile/2806729|title=Samira Kiani {{!}} iSearch|website=isearch.asu.edu|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kianilab.com/about-us.html|title=About Us|website=Kiani Lab|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She was awarded a [[DARPA]] fellowship to investigate hearing loss caused by [[Traumatic injuries|traumatic injuries]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20160926-looking-bigger-roles-game-changing-leaps-tech-capabilities|title=Looking for bigger roles in game-changing leaps in tech capabilities|date=2016-09-26|website=ASU Now: Access, Excellence, Impact|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> The loud noises of combat zones can result in a health threat to military personnel.<ref name=\":3\" /> Kiani works on safer gene therapies, including [[Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeat]] ([[CRISPR]]). The [[Cas9]] protein works to cleave DNA, and can be targeted using a [[Guide RNA|gRNA]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kianilab.com/research.html|title=Research|website=Kiani Lab|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> When the [[Guide RNA|gRNA]] reaches the target site it performs a double strand break, enabling gene disruption or editing.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Kiani lab looks to control where and when this gene disruption occurs. She has investigated whether [[CRISPR]] could be used to restore [[Hearing loss|hearing loss]] after [[Acoustic trauma|acoustic trauma]] and [[aminoglycoside]].<ref name=\":4\" /> She working on the optimisation of [[CRISPR gene editing]] using [[RNA polymerase II|RNA pol II]].<ref name=\":4\" /> She has discussed her work on the Future Tech podcast.<ref>{{Citation|last=Future Tech Podcast|title=Amazing Genes \u2013 Samira Kiani, M.D. (PI), Kiani Lab, Arizona State University \u2013 Gene Editing Technolo|date=2018-07-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcSvoMHoM6A|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> \n\nHer research is also supported by two grants from National Institute of Health, the most recent one being $2,600,000 from the [[National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kiani|first=Samira|title=CRISPR logic circuits for safer and controllable gene therapies|url=http://grantome.com/grant/NIH/R01-EB024562-01A1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/10/181014142714.htm|title=Liver-on-a-chip, the ideal test environment for CRISPR|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> The proposal looks to develop a human liver-on-a-chip using [[CRISPR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-10/asu-lti101118.php|title=Liver-on-a-chip, the ideal test environment for CRISPR|website=EurekAlert!|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20181012-liver-chip-ideal-test-environment-crispr|title=Liver-on-a-chip, the ideal test environment for CRISPR|date=2018-10-12|website=ASU Now: Access, Excellence, Impact|language=en|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Public engagement ===\nIn 2019 Kiani was announced as a Leshner Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaas.org/programs/center-public-engagement-science-and-technology/2019-2020-leshner-leadership-institute|title=2019-2020 Leshner Leadership Institute Public Engagement Fellows: Human Augmentation|website=American Association for the Advancement of Science|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She is working with [[Cody Sheehy]] to create a documentary entitled ''The Human Game.'' Kiani serves as the co-producer on the project, which looks to create a deeper discussion between the public and scientists about CRISPR technologies. In addition, together with Cody Sheehy, they are promoting a public engagement initiative called Tomorrow.Life aimed at increasing participation of broader stakeholders in decisions about future of science through collaborative visual story telling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://codeofthewild.org/people/|title=Advisors & Team|website=Code of the Wild|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiani, Samira}}\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Iranian scientists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women academics]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tehran University of Medical Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Health systems engineer}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Samira Kiani\n| alma_mater = [[Tehran University of Medical Sciences]] <br>\n| workplaces = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] <br> [[Arizona State University]]\n| known_for = [[CRISPR]]\n}}\n\n'''Samira Kiani''' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0627 \u06a9\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}) is an Associate Professor in the department of Pathology of University of Pittsburgh, School of Medicine and Pittsburgh Liver Research Center. Fromerly, she was a Health Systems Engineer at [[Arizona State University]]. Her work combines [[Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeat]] ([[CRISPR]]) with synthetic biology. She is a 2019 [[American Association for the Advancement of Science|AAAS]] Leshner Fellow.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKiani is from [[Iran]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://innercircle.engineering.asu.edu/2016/03/01/meet-your-new-sbhse-faculty/|title=Meet your new SBHSE faculty {{!}} Inner Circle|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She earned her medical degree at the [[Tehran University of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://theinnovationinstitute.org/samira-kiani|title=Samira Kiani|website=TheInnovationInstitute.Org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She completed a thesis on the molecular mechanisms of tissue injury.<ref name=\":1\" /> She joined the [[Freeman Hospital]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], where she was trained in general medicine.<ref name=\":1\" /> She joined the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], working as a postdoctoral researcher in [[Synthetic biology|synthetic biology]] at MIT Synthetic Biology Center.<ref name=\":1\" /> She has acted as an advisor for the [[MIT]] International Genetically Engineered Machine (iGEM) team.<ref name=\":1\" /> She collaborated with George Church and Ron Weiss to advance [[CRISPR]] technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiche.org/community/bio/samira-kiani|title=Samira Kiani|date=2017-10-19|website=www.aiche.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Weiss|first=Ron|last2=Li|first2=Yinqing|last3=Xie|first3=Zhen|last4=Richard N. Hall|last5=Huh|first5=Jin|last6=Ebrahimkhani|first6=Mohammad R.|last7=Beal|first7=Jacob|last8=Kiani|first8=Samira|date=2014|title=CRISPR transcriptional repression devices and layered circuits in mammalian cells|journal=Nature Methods|language=en|volume=11|issue=7|pages=723\u2013726|doi=10.1038/nmeth.2969|pmid=24797424|issn=1548-7105|pmc=4228775}}</ref> They developed a [[CRISPR]] based a modular transcriptional repression architecture that can be used to create functional cascaded circuits.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Research and career ==\nKiani joined [[Arizona State University]] in 2016 and later moved to University of Pittsburgh in January 2020.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isearch.asu.edu/profile/2806729|title=Samira Kiani {{!}} iSearch|website=isearch.asu.edu|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kianilab.com/about-us.html|title=About Us|website=Kiani Lab|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She was awarded a [[DARPA]] fellowship to investigate hearing loss caused by [[Traumatic injuries|traumatic injuries]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20160926-looking-bigger-roles-game-changing-leaps-tech-capabilities|title=Looking for bigger roles in game-changing leaps in tech capabilities|date=2016-09-26|website=ASU Now: Access, Excellence, Impact|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> The loud noises of combat zones can result in a health threat to military personnel.<ref name=\":3\" /> Kiani works on safer gene therapies, including [[Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeat]] ([[CRISPR]]). The [[Cas9]] protein works to cleave DNA, and can be targeted using a [[Guide RNA|gRNA]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kianilab.com/research.html|title=Research|website=Kiani Lab|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> When the [[Guide RNA|gRNA]] reaches the target site it performs a double strand break, enabling gene disruption or editing.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Kiani lab looks to control where and when this gene disruption occurs. She has investigated whether [[CRISPR]] could be used to restore [[Hearing loss|hearing loss]] after [[Acoustic trauma|acoustic trauma]] and [[aminoglycoside]].<ref name=\":4\" /> She working on the optimisation of [[CRISPR gene editing]] using [[RNA polymerase II|RNA pol II]].<ref name=\":4\" /> She has discussed her work on the Future Tech podcast.<ref>{{Citation|last=Future Tech Podcast|title=Amazing Genes \u2013 Samira Kiani, M.D. (PI), Kiani Lab, Arizona State University \u2013 Gene Editing Technolo|date=2018-07-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcSvoMHoM6A|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> \n\nHer research is also supported by two grants from National Institute of Health, the most recent one being $2,600,000 from the [[National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kiani|first=Samira|title=CRISPR logic circuits for safer and controllable gene therapies|url=http://grantome.com/grant/NIH/R01-EB024562-01A1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/10/181014142714.htm|title=Liver-on-a-chip, the ideal test environment for CRISPR|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> The proposal looks to develop a human liver-on-a-chip using [[CRISPR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-10/asu-lti101118.php|title=Liver-on-a-chip, the ideal test environment for CRISPR|website=EurekAlert!|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20181012-liver-chip-ideal-test-environment-crispr|title=Liver-on-a-chip, the ideal test environment for CRISPR|date=2018-10-12|website=ASU Now: Access, Excellence, Impact|language=en|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Public engagement ===\nIn 2019 Kiani was announced as a Leshner Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaas.org/programs/center-public-engagement-science-and-technology/2019-2020-leshner-leadership-institute|title=2019-2020 Leshner Leadership Institute Public Engagement Fellows: Human Augmentation|website=American Association for the Advancement of Science|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> She is working with [[Cody Sheehy]] to create a documentary entitled ''The Human Game.'' Kiani serves as the co-producer on the project, which looks to create a deeper discussion between the public and scientists about [[CRISPR]] technologies.In addition, together with Cody Sheehy they are promoting a public engagement initiative called Tomorrow.Life aimed at increasing participation of broader stakeholders in decisions about future of science through collaborative visual story telling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://codeofthewild.org/people/|title=Advisors & Team|website=Code of the Wild|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiani, Samira}}\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Iranian scientists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women academics]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Arizona State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Tehran University of Medical Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samira_Kiani"}
{"title_page": "2012 Pan American Men's Handball Championship", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox international handball competition\n| tourney_name = Pan American Men's Handball Championship\n| year = 2012\n| yearr = \n| other_titles = PanAmericano 2012\n| image =\n| size = \n| caption = \n| country = Argentina\n| dates = 18\u201324 June\n| num_teams = 9\n| confederations = 1\n| venues = 1\n| cities = 1\n| champion = ARG\n| count = 5\n| second = BRA\n| third = CHI\n| fourth = URU\n| matches = 23\n| goals = 1227\n| attendance = \n| top_scorer = {{flagicon|GRL}} [[Minik Dahl H\u00f8egh]]<br><small>(49 goals)</small>\n| player = {{flagicon|CHI}} [[Marco Oneto]]\n| previous = 2010 Pan American Men's Handball Championship\n| next = 2014 Pan American Men's Handball Championship\n}}\n\nThe '''2012 [[Pan American Handball Championship]]''', also called '''PanAmericano 2012''', was the 15th official competition for senior men's national [[Team handball|handball]] teams of North, Center, Caribbean and South America. It was held from 18\u201324 June 2012 in [[Burzaco]], [[Almirante Brown Partido]], [[Argentina]]. It also acted as the qualifying competition for the [[2013 World Men's Handball Championship]], securing three vacancies for the World Championship. A decision was announced during the [[2011 Pan American Games]] that the tournament will consist of 12 teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://teamhandballnews.com/2011/10/new-developments-regarding-pathf-competitions/|title=New developments regarding PATHF competitions|date=23 October 2011|work=teamhandballnews.com}}</ref> As the winner of those Pan American Games, Argentina was selected as the host.\n\n== Participating teams ==\nThe participating nations have been announced on 15 May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panamhandball.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=174&Itemid=1|title=Confirmados diez pa\u00edses al Campeonato masculino adulto 2012|date=15 May 2012|work=panamhandball.org|access-date=19 May 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120913092623/http://www.panamhandball.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=174&Itemid=1#|archive-date=13 September 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=50%|Group A\n!width=50%|Group B\n|- \n|valign=top|\n{{hb|ARG}}<br />\n{{hb|CHI}}<br />\n{{hb|GRL}}<br />\n{{hb|USA}}<br />\n{{hb|VEN}}\n|valign=top|\n{{hb|BRA}}<br />\n<s>{{hb|DOM}}</s><br />\n{{hb|MEX}}<br />\n{{hb|PAR}}<br />\n{{hb|URU}}\n|}\n\nThe Dominican Republic team withdrew after the draw, reportedly for financial reasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Men\u2019s WC Qual|url=http://teamhandballnews.com/wordpress/2013-mens-wc-qual/|publisher=teamhandballnews.com|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Preliminary round==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|Team advances to the [[#Final round|Semifinals]]\n|-\n| style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|Team will play [[#Placement matches|Placement Matches]]\n|}\n\n''All times are local ([[Time in Argentina|UTC\u22123]])''\n\n===Group A===\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=Q\n|winpoints=2\n|show_positions=n\n\n|team1=ARG|name_ARG={{hb|ARG}}\n|team2=CHI|name_CHI={{hb|CHI}}\n|team3=GRL|name_GRL={{hb|GRL}}\n|team4=USA|name_USA={{hb|USA}}\n|team5=VEN|name_VEN={{hb|VEN}}\n|win_ARG=3|draw_ARG=1|loss_ARG=0|gf_ARG=127|ga_ARG=69\n|win_CHI=3|draw_CHI=1|loss_CHI=0|gf_CHI=123|ga_CHI=95\n|win_GRL=2|draw_GRL=0|loss_GRL=2|gf_GRL=123|ga_GRL=117\n|win_USA=1|draw_USA=0|loss_USA=3|gf_USA=102|ga_USA=132\n|win_VEN=0|draw_VEN=0|loss_VEN=4|gf_VEN=103|ga_VEN=165\n\n|col_A=green1|text_A=\n|result1=A|result2=A\n|col_E=red1|text_E=\n|result3=E|result4=E|result5=E\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n{{handballbox \n|date= 18 June 2012\n|time= 18:00\n|team1= {{hb-rt|ARG}}\n|score= 33 \u2013 13\n|team2= {{hb|USA}}\n|report= [http://www.handballargentina.org/escuela/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Planilla-de-