{"title_page": "Advanced Gravis Computer Technology", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}[[File:Gravis gamepad.jpg|thumb|[[Gravis Gamepad]].]]\n'''Advanced Gravis Computer Technology, Ltd.''' was a manufacturer of computer [[peripheral]]s and [[computer hardware|hardware]]. The company was founded in 1982 in [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]].\n\nTheir most famous products were the [[Gravis PC GamePad]], at one time one of the most popular [[game controller|gaming controllers]] for the PC,<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=Get a Grip!!!: Joysticks Past, Present & Future |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=17|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=May 1996|page=39}}</ref> the once-ubiquitous Gravis Joystick (black with red buttons), and the [[Gravis Ultrasound]] add-on card, competitor to the [[Sound Blaster]]. At its peak, the company had almost 300 employees with a European office in The Netherlands, and was at the time the world's largest manufacturer of computer joysticks and gamepads.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe company was acquired by [[Kensington Computer Products Group]] in 1997<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://immr.client.shareholder.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=111458|title=Immersion and Gravis Partner to Create New Force Feedback Devices; Innovative Technology Extends Opportunities for Developers|date=2000-03-10|accessdate=2009-10-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202940/http://immr.client.shareholder.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=111458|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=dead}}\n</ref> and has essentially disappeared.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- dead link *[http://sec.edgar-online.com/1996/07/31/00/0000891020-96-000814/Section2.asp 1996 company fiscal report] -->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19980420184218/http://ftp.gravis.com/ ftp.gravis.com] drivers\n\n[[Category:Computer peripheral companies]]\n[[Category:Computer companies established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Companies based in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in British Columbia]]\n\n\n{{Canada-videogame-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2019}}[[File:Gravis gamepad.jpg|thumb|[[Gravis Gamepad]].]]\n'''Advanced Gravis Computer Technology, Ltd.''' was a manufacturer of computer [[peripheral]]s and [[computer hardware|hardware]]. The company was founded in 1982 in [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]].\n\nTheir most famous products were the [[Gravis PC GamePad]], at one time one of the most popular [[game controller|gaming controllers]] for the PC,<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=Get a Grip!!!: Joysticks Past, Present & Future |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=17|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=May 1996|page=39}}</ref> the once-ubiquitous Gravis Joystick (black with red buttons), and the [[Gravis Ultrasound]] add-on card, competitor to the [[Sound Blaster]]. At its peak, the company had almost 300 employees with an European office in The Netherlands, and was at the time the world's largest manufacturer of computer joysticks and gamepads.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe company was acquired by [[Kensington Computer Products Group]] in 1997<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://immr.client.shareholder.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=111458|title=Immersion and Gravis Partner to Create New Force Feedback Devices; Innovative Technology Extends Opportunities for Developers|date=2000-03-10|accessdate=2009-10-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202940/http://immr.client.shareholder.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=111458|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=dead}}\n</ref> and has essentially disappeared.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- dead link *[http://sec.edgar-online.com/1996/07/31/00/0000891020-96-000814/Section2.asp 1996 company fiscal report] -->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19980420184218/http://ftp.gravis.com/ ftp.gravis.com]