{"title_page": "Bruno Mars at Park Theater at Park MGM", "text_new": "{{short description|Residency show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox concert\n|concert_tour_name = Bruno Mars at Park Theater at Park MGM\n|image             =\n|image_size        =\n|alt               =\n|caption           =\n|artist            = [[Bruno Mars]]\n|location          = [[Park Theater (Las Vegas)|Park Theater]], [[Park MGM]] <br />[[Las Vegas]], Nevada, U.S.<br /> [[MGM National Harbor|The Theater at MGM National Harbor]] <br />[[Oxon Hill]], Maryland, U.S.\n|type              = Concert residency\n|start_date        = {{Start date|2016|12|27}}\n|end_date          = {{End date|2020|4|25}}\n|number_of_legs    = 8\n|number_of_shows   = 34\n|attendance        = 121,857\n|gross             = $29 million\n|website           =\n|last_tour         = [[Bruno Mars at The Chelsea at The Cosmopolitan]]<br />(2013\u20132015)\n|this_tour         = '''Bruno Mars at Park Theater at Park MGM'''<br />(2016\u20132020)\n|next_tour         = [[24K Magic World Tour]]<br />(2017\u20132018)\n}}\n\n'''Bruno Mars at Park Theater at Park MGM''' is a [[concert residency]] held at the [[Park Theater (Las Vegas)|Park Theater]], [[Park MGM]] in [[Las Vegas]] and [[MGM National Harbor|The Theater at MGM National Harbor]], [[Oxon Hill]] in Maryland by American singer and songwriter [[Bruno Mars]]. Both venues are located in the United States. The setlist, which featured songs from ''[[Doo-Wops & Hooligans]]'' (2010), ''[[Unorthodox Jukebox]]'' (2012), ''[[24K Magic (album)|24K Magic]]'' (2016) and various covers, was performed by Mars, backed by his eight-piece band, The Hooligans. The concert residency was promoted by Live Nation and MGM Resorts, lasted four years and grossed $29 million. The April 2020 dates were cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in China and its spread to other countries.\n\n==Background and development==\nOn October 10, 2016, ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' announced that Mars signed a two-year deal with MGM Resorts International to perform at the [[Park MGM|Park Theater]] at [[Monte Carlo]], in Las Vegas and The Theater at [[MGM National Harbor]], in Maryland.<ref name=\"ETRM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/news/199972_exclusive_bruno_mars_partners_with_mgm_resorts_international_for_the_next_two_years|title=Exclusive: Bruno Mars Partners With MGM Resorts International for the Next Two Years|last=McRady|first=Rachel|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=October 10, 2016|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> This was Mars second concert residency, after performing at [[Bruno Mars at The Chelsea at The Cosmopolitan|The Chelsea at The Cosmopolitan]] with the last show being 2015 New Year's Eve.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8494910/bruno-mars-maroon-5-las-vegas-new-years-eve-sales|title=Bruno Mars & Maroon 5 Leave Las Vegas With Their Biggest New Year's Eve Jackpots Yet|last=Frankenberg|first=Eric|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billbord]]|date=January 24, 2019|accessdate=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125025924/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8494910/bruno-mars-maroon-5-las-vegas-new-years-eve-sales|archivedate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> The president of MGM Resorts International, Bill Hornbuckle, said \"There is no stronger launching pad for a new venue than for Mars to be among the first to grace its stage\".<ref name=\"ETRM\"/> The singer was among first to perform at the MGM National Harbor, as well as the first to perform at the new Park Theater, which features 5,300 seats, as well as brand new audio and visual technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2016/10/10/bruno-mars-open-theater-mgm-casino-national-harbor/|title=Bruno Mars to Open Theater in MGM Casino at National Harbor|last=Freed|first=Benjamin|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|date=October 10, 2016|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ktnv.com/positivelylv/dining-and-entertainment/bruno-mars-performing-in-las-vegas-for-new-years-eve|title=Bruno Mars performing in Las Vegas for New Year's Eve|publisher=[[KTNV-TV]]|date=October 10, 2016|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The concert residency was promoted by Live Nation and occasionally by MGM Resorts.<ref name=\"BBBIZ1\"/><ref name=\"BBBIZ2\"/><ref name=\"BBBIZ4\"/> \n\n==Shows cancellation==\nThe ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' reported that Mars avoid contact the fans on his shows on March 6 and 7, 2020, at the Park Theater, as a response to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/cirque-du-soleil-halts-touring-shows-in-coronavirus-response-1977897/|title=Cirque du Soleil halts touring shows in coronavirus response|last=Katsilometes|first=John|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020|url-access=subscription|url-status=live}}</ref> Moreover, MGM Resorts announced the cancellation of the dates at the Park Theater on April 20, 24, and 25 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in China and its spread to other countries.<ref name=\"JKLVRJ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/bruno-mars-cuts-1m-check-to-mgm-resorts-assistance-fund-1991797/|title=Bruno Mars cuts $1M check to MGM Resorts assistance fund|last=Katsilometes|first=John|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis and reception==\nThe concert, which had a runtime of 95 minutes opened with \"24K Magic\" and an advertisement for Las Vegas.\nDuring the show, Mars split the fans in half \"to see who was loudest\". During the concert \"[[Runaway Baby]]\" was interluded with [[The Isley Brothers]]'s \"[[Shout (Isley Brothers song)|Shout]]\" as Mars sung \"A little bit softer now...\" him and his band fell to the ground, only to rose up again closing the track. There was also a mash-up of Barrett Strong's \"[[Money (That's What I Want)]]\" and [[Travie McCoy]]'s featuring Mars \"[[Billionaire (song)|Billionaire]]\". He also covered \"[[Pony (Ginuwine song)|Pony]]\" by [[Ginuwine]], gave \"[[Grenade (song)|Grenade]]\" a guitar solo transforming it into a rock song and performed the ballad \"[[When I Was Your Man]]\". At one point he asked the crowd if they could not look at their phones for a while. During the New Year's end concert as they were ending the performance of \"[[Locked Out of Heaven]]\", \"the power went out onstage\". The show closed with \"[[Uptown Funk]]\". The concert included fire cannons and a \"giant sign spelling out\" Bruno Mars.<ref name=\"LVRJMW\"/> \n\nMike Weatherford from ''Las Vegas Review-Journal'', while reviewing Mars' 2017 New Years concert, noticed the wide range of people's age and stated \"If the casinos could genetically engineer the perfect entertainment machine, Mars is it.\" Weatherford gave the show an A rating.<ref name=\"LVRJMW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/mike-weatherford/bruno-mars-keeps-the-party-from-getting-too-predictable/|title=Bruno Mars keeps the party from getting too predictable|last=Weatherford|first=Mike|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=January 1, 2017|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url-access=subscription|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lasvegasweekly.com/ae/music/2018/feb/20/bruno-mars-park-theater-las-vegas-strip/|title=Bruno Mars Can Have Begas Whenever He Wants|last=Radke|first=Brock|work=Las Vegas Weekly|date=February 20, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/phones-locked-up-during-bruno-mars-concert-on-las-vegas-strip/|title=Phones locked up during Bruno Mars concert on Las Vegas Strip|last=Katsilometes|first=John|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=July 28, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url-access=subscription|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Shows==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of concerts, showing date, city, venue, tickets sold, amount of available tickets and gross revenue\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| City\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Venue\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Attendance\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Revenue\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\"| Leg 1<ref name=\"BBBIZ1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 15, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315234758/https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|archivedate=March 15, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| December 27, 2016\n| [[National Harbor, Maryland|National Harbor]] \n| [[MGM National Harbor|The Theater at MGM National Harbor]] \n| 2,646 /2,746\n| $582,275\n|-\t\n| December 30, 2016\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Las Vegas\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Monte Carlo Resort and Casino|The Park Theater]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 10,157 / 11,000\n|rowspan=\"2\"| $2,547,397\n|-\n| December 31, 2016\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\"| Leg 2<ref name=\"BBBIZ2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 13, 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?id=1491600892346950|archivedate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 11, 2017\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Las Vegas\n|rowspan=\"2\"| The Park Theater\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 10,466 / 10,466\n|rowspan=\"2\"|$2,158,850\n|-\n| March 12, 2017\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\"| Leg 3<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore |title=Billboard Boxscore :: Current Scores|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 13, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914185432/http://www.billboard.co