ospitalised on 23 March 2020.\n|-\n| 58\n| 2210\n| 4 April 2020\n| {{MYS}}\n| Male\n| 72\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Sarawak.svg}} Sarawak General Hospital\n| Close contact of case number 1031 (fifth death case). Had chronic illness. Hospitalised on 27 March 2020.\n| rowspan=\"4\" | <ref name=\"my0405\"/>\n|-\n| 59\n| 3484\n| 4 April 2020\n| {{MYS}}\n| Male\n| 68\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Kuala Lumpur Malaysia.svg}} Kuala Lumpur Hospital\n| Had chronic illness. Hospitalised on 27 March 2020.\n|-\n| 60\n| 3073\n| 5 April 2020\n| {{MYS}}\n| Male\n| 53\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Sarawak.svg}} Sarawak General Hospital\n| Hospitalised on 31 March 2020.\n|-\n| 61\n| 2200\n| 4 April 2020\n| {{MYS}}\n| Male\n| 66\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Sabah.svg}} Keningau Hospital\n| Had chronic illness. Hospitalised on 26 March 2020.\n|}\n\n== Case-related events ==\n=== January 2020 ===\nEight Chinese nationals were quarantined at a hotel in [[Johor Bahru]] on 24 January after coming into contact with an [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore|infected person]] in neighbouring [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"Wuhan virus\"/> Despite early reports of them testing negative for the virus,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/24/johor-baru-eight-chinese-tourists-show-no-coronavirus-symptoms/1831224|title=Eight Chinese tourists show no coronavirus symptoms in Johor Baru|agency=Bernama|work=The Malay Mail|date=24 January 2020|accessdate=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217122850/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/24/johor-baru-eight-chinese-tourists-show-no-coronavirus-symptoms/1831224|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> three of them were confirmed to be infected on 25 January and subsequently quarantined at the [[Sungai Buloh Hospital]] in Selangor.<ref name=\"confirmed COVID-19\"/><ref name=\"three Chinese nationals confirmed COVID-19\"/> The [[Ministry of Health (Malaysia)|Malaysian health ministry]] published guidelines on the virus and established designated hospitals in each of [[States and federal territories of Malaysia#States|Malaysia's states]] to manage any positive cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mpaeds.my/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Guidelines-2019-Novel-Coronavirus-2019-nCoV-Management-In-Malaysia-No.-22020.pdf|title=Guidelines on the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) Management in Malaysia|work=Ministry of Health, Malaysia|via=Malaysian Paediatric Association|year=2020|accessdate=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217134220/https://mpaeds.my/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Guidelines-2019-Novel-Coronavirus-2019-nCoV-Management-In-Malaysia-No.-22020.pdf|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Malaysian public were reminded by local authorities to take precautionary measures in the wake of the virus threat with those travelling to China have been advised to stay away from animal farms and markets in the country and to not eat raw or semi-cooked meats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/g/214976|title=On high alert against coronavirus|last=Majid|first=Irwan|work=The Malaysian Insight|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126045754/https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/g/214976|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following several earlier suspected cases in [[Sabah]]'s capital of [[Kota Kinabalu]], all direct flights between the state with China were stopped indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/24/flights-to-wuhan-cancelled|title=Flights to Wuhan cancelled|work=The Star|date=24 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130001423/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/24/flights-to-wuhan-cancelled|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/30/wuhan-coronavirus-all-flights-from-china-to-sabah-suspended-as-state-govt-imposes-travel-ban/|title=Wuhan coronavirus: All flights from China to Sabah suspended as state govt imposes travel ban|work=Borneo Post|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201050803/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/30/wuhan-coronavirus-all-flights-from-china-to-sabah-suspended-as-state-govt-imposes-travel-ban/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January, a two-year-old child who was suspected to have been infected was detained along with their parents. The parents refused quarantine and were detained the next day by police at [[Senai International Airport]] before returning to China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/26/wuhan-virus-chinese-toddler-parents-who-dodged-quarantine-in-johor-detained|title=Wuhan virus: Chinese toddler, parents who dodged quarantine in Johor detained|last=Devi|first=Venesa|work=The Star|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126060351/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/26/wuhan-virus-chinese-toddler-parents-who-dodged-quarantine-in-johor-detained|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The patient including others who refused quarantine were subsequently placed under close monitoring by the local Health Ministry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/02/health-ministry-no-new-positive-cases-in-malaysia|title=Health Ministry: No new positive cases in Malaysia|work=The Star|date=2 February 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202015654/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/02/health-ministry-no-new-positive-cases-in-malaysia|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 January, a fourth case of the virus, unconnected to previous cases, was detected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/wuhan-virus-malaysia-fourth-confirmed-case-12340042 |title=Malaysia reports fourth confirmed case of Wuhan virus|work=CNA|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125235527/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/wuhan-virus-malaysia-fourth-confirmed-case-12340042|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A suspected case was also detected in the state of [[Kedah]]'s [[Langkawi Island|island of Langkawi]] involving two female Chinese nationals with both victims quarantined at the Sultanah Maliha Hospital; one later confirmed positive on 29 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/559950/langkawi-quarantines-two-chinese-girls-suspected-coronavirus-infection|title=Langkawi quarantines two Chinese girls suspected of coronavirus infection|last=Osman|first=Hamzah|work=New Straits Times|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126142818/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/559950/langkawi-quarantines-two-chinese-girls-suspected-coronavirus-infection|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/26/wuhan-virus-toddlers-from-china-quarantined-at-langkawi-hospital|title=Siblings suspected of contracting Wuhan virus quarantined in Langkawi Hospital|last=Hilmy|first=Imran|work=The Star|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126143148/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/26/wuhan-virus-toddlers-from-china-quarantined-at-langkawi-hospital|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Coronavirus Langkawi and Bintulu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/1-woman-from-bintulu-2-children-in-langkawi-suspected-to-be-infected-with-deadly-wuhan-virus/|title=1 Woman From Bintulu & 2 Children in Langkawi Suspected To Be Infected With Deadly Wuhan Virus|last=Liew|first=Esther|work=World of Buzz|date=27 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130031741/https://www.worldofbuzz.com/1-woman-from-bintulu-2-children-in-langkawi-suspected-to-be-infected-with-deadly-wuhan-virus/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"three more positive cases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1809869|title=Coronavirus: Three more positive cases in Malaysia, bringing total to seven|agency=Bernama|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129164930/http://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1809869|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the increasing number of cases reported in neighbouring Thailand, both the state of Kedah and [[Penang]] tightened their borders by conducting stringent checks at its international entry points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/25/penang-kedah-conducting-stringent-checks-at-entry-points|title=Penang, Kedah conducting stringent checks at entry points|last=Hilmy|first=Imran|work=The Star|date=25 January 2020|accessdate=26 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125142658/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/25/penang-kedah-conducting-stringent-checks-at-entry-points|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A Chinese female national in [[Bintulu]] of [[Sarawak]] also suspected of having contracted the virus led to the state tightening its border and postponing direct flights to [[Hainan]], despite a recently signed [[memorandum of understanding]] (MoU) establishing direct flights with Sarawak.<ref name=\"Coronavirus Langkawi and Bintulu\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/26/abdul-karim-looking-into-postponing-direct-flights-to-hainan-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|title=Abdul Karim looking into postponing direct flights to Hainan due to Coronavirus outbreak in China|last=David|first=Jacqueline|agency=Bernama|work=Borneo Post|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201050801/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/01/26/abdul-karim-looking-into-postponing-direct-flights-to-hainan-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/01/27/suspected-case-of-coronavirus-detected-in-bintulu-says-minister/|title=Suspected case of coronavirus detected in Bintulu, says minister|last=Abu Bakar|first=Adam|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=27 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128173536/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/01/27/suspected-case-of-coronavirus-detected-in-bintulu-says-minister/|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/27/mb-sarawak-to-tighten-gateway-along-malaysia-brunei-border-following-corona/1831868|title=MB: Sarawak to tighten gateway along Malaysia-Brunei border following coronavirus outbreak|agency=Bernama|work=The Malay Mail|date=27 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201050752/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/27/mb-sarawak-to-tighten-gateway-along-malaysia-brunei-border-following-corona/1831868|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOf the total of 25 Chinese nationals in Sabah earlier suspected of having contracted the virus, most of them tested negative as of 28 January although one of them later tested positive for the virus upon reaching China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/30/coronavirus-25-people-test-negative-in-sabah-says-state-health-dept|title=Coronavirus: 25 people test negative in Sabah, says state Health Dept|last=Inus|first=Kristy|work=The Star|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202021119/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/30/coronavirus-25-people-test-negative-in-sabah-says-state-health-dept|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/561037/tianjin-tourist-sabah-likely-have-contracted-coronavirus-china|title=Tianjin tourist in Sabah likely to have contracted coronavirus in China|last1=Miwil|first1=Olivia|last2=Dahali|first2=Rafiqah|work=New Straits Times|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202021120/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/561037/tianjin-tourist-sabah-likely-have-contracted-coronavirus-china|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another four suspected cases were recorded in Sarawak on 29 January; five in [[Kuching]] and one each in [[Sibu]] and [[Miri, Malaysia|Miri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dayakdaily.com/8-suspected-cases-of-wuhan-virus-recorded-in-sarawak-so-far/|title=[UPDATED] 8 suspected cases of Wuhan virus recorded in Sarawak so far|last=Nais|first=Nancy|work=Dayak Daily|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202015658/https://dayakdaily.com/8-suspected-cases-of-wuhan-virus-recorded-in-sarawak-so-far/|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Of the total eight suspected cases in the state, six have tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/29/sarawak-dcm-says-six-of-eight-suspected-coronavirus-cases-in-state-cleared/1832449|title=Sarawak DCM says six of eight suspected coronavirus cases in state cleared|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202020030/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/29/sarawak-dcm-says-six-of-eight-suspected-coronavirus-cases-in-state-cleared/1832449|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Within the same day, three additional positive cases were confirmed in [[West Malaysia]], involving a four-year-old child quarantined at the Sultanah Maliha Hospital in [[Kedah]], a 52-year-old man at [[Sultanah Aminah Hospital]] in Johor and a woman at [[Sungai Buloh Hospital]] in Selangor.<ref name=\"three more positive cases\"/> An eighth case was reported at the Permai Hospital in Johor on the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/koronavirus-satu-lagi-kes-positif-dikesan-di-malaysia-229384|title=Koronavirus: Satu lagi kes positif dikesan di Malaysia|trans-title=Coronavirus: Another positive case detected in Malaysia|last=Danial Razi|first=Faris|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130090404/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/koronavirus-satu-lagi-kes-positif-dikesan-di-malaysia-229384|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== February 2020 ===\nOn 4 February, Malaysia announced two new cases, including a 41-year-old local male, which was the first case involving a Malaysian. The case patient had a recent trip to Singapore and is quarantined in Sungai Buloh Hospital. The other case involved a 63-year-old male from China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_coronavirus.php?id=1811373|title=First case of Malaysian positive for coronavirus|agency=Bernama|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the child quarantined at the Sultanah Maliha Hospital had made a full recovery, was discharged, and allowed to return to China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1811559|title=Chinese girl recovers from coronavirus, discharged from hospital|agency=Bernama|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> On 5 February, two of 107 Malaysians and non-Malaysian family relatives brought back from Wuhan by the Malaysian government tested positive and were quarantined at [[Tuanku Ja'afar Hospital]] in [[Seremban]] of [[Negeri Sembilan]]. They were a 45-year-old man and his nine-year-old son, both Malaysians, bringing the total to 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1811690|title=Two Malaysian evacuees from Wuhan positive for coronavirus \u2013 Health Minister|agency=Bernama|date=5 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The younger sister of the 41-year-old Malaysian reported positive of the virus on 4 February, a 40-year-old Malaysian had also been confirmed infected with the virus on 6 February, making her the first patient who acquired the virus through local transmission in Malaysia, and warded at Sultanah Bahiyah Hospital in [[Alor Setar]]. A positive case involving a 32-year-old woman from Wuhan was reported on the same day. The woman came to Malaysia on 25 January and referred to [[Kuala Lumpur Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1811990|title=Coronavirus: Malaysia records first local transmission|agency=Bernama|date=6 February 2020|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> Another woman from Wuhan was confirmed positive of the virus on the next day, and was quarantined in Hospital Permai with her husband, who was asymptomatic. The 59-year-old woman came from Malaysia from Singapore on 21 January with three of her relatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1812212|title=Coronavirus: Malaysia confirms another positive case, tally rises to 15|agency=Bernama|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February, Malaysia reported an another case involving a Wuhan tourist. The case patient is a 67-year-old woman who had indirect relations with another case patient reported positive on 6 February and quarantined at Kuala Lumpur Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1812481|title=Malaysia confirms 16th case of coronavirus|agency=Bernama|date=8 February 2020|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Malaysia reported that its fourth case patient, who was warded at Permai Hospital had acquired a full recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/563769/man-40-second-patient-malaysia-recover-coronavirus|title=Man, 40, second patient in Malaysia to recover from coronavirus|website=New Straits Times|date=8 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217123614/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/563769/man-40-second-patient-malaysia-recover-coronavirus|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 11 new patients were also admitted to hospitals within the day for investigation of suspected infection in the state of [[Sarawak]] after they were reported to show symptoms; they comprised nine in [[Sibu Hospital]], one in [[Miri Hospital]] and one in [[Sarawak General Hospital]] of Kuching. A hotline was subsequently set up by the Sarawak state government on the virus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/09/sarawak-health-dept-sets-up-coronavirus-hotline|title=Sarawak Health Dept sets up coronavirus hotline|last=Then|first=Stephen|work=The Star|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217123814/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/09/sarawak-health-dept-sets-up-coronavirus-hotline|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 February, the mother-in-law of the ninth case, a 65-year-old local became the 17th reported case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1812617|title=Elderly woman the latest and 17th coronavirus case \u2013 Health DG|agency=Bernama|date=9 February 2020|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, Malaysia reported its third full recovery involving its tenth case patient on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1812643|title=Coronavirus: third case of full recovery, patient to be discharged from HKL|agency=Bernama|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> On 10 February, Malaysia reported its 18th case,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1812709|title=Local man is latest coronavirus positive case|agency=Bernama|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-malaysia-confirms-sixth-citizen-case-macau-12415998|title=Malaysia confirms sixth citizen case of coronavirus, man worked in Macau before coming home unwell|last=Yusof|first=Amir|work=CNA|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=10 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217124102/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-malaysia-confirms-sixth-citizen-case-macau-12415998|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> a 31-year-old local who worked in Macau until 1 February. The same day, the Sarawak Disaster Management Committee began to impose a prohibition to neighbouring Singaporeans due to the major increase of positive cases in the neighbouring country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiaairlines.com/content/dam/mas/pdf/SARAWAK%20STATE%20DISASTER%20MANAGEMENT%20COMMITTEE-SINGAPOREANS%20COMING%20FOR%20SHOR....pdf|title=Singaporeans Coming for Short Term Visit Must Abide by the Health Ministry Guidelines: SDMC|publisher=Sarawak Disaster Management Committee|via=Malaysia Airlines|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215033921/https://www.malaysiaairlines.com/content/dam/mas/pdf/SARAWAK%20STATE%20DISASTER%20MANAGEMENT%20COMMITTEE-SINGAPOREANS%20COMING%20FOR%20SHOR....pdf|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Temporary Travel Restrictions into Malaysia as released by Malaysia Airlines.jpg|thumb|upright=2|right|Temporary travel restrictions into Malaysia on 13 February 2020, particularly to the states of [[Sabah]] and [[Sarawak]] as released by [[Malaysia Airlines]].]]\nOn 13 February, Malaysia reported its 19th case, which is a 39-year-old woman from Wuhan and daughter of the 16th case patient, warded at Kuala Lumpur Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2216462.html|title=\u5927\u9a6c\u65b0\u589e\u7b2c19\u5b97\u786e\u8bca|trans-title=19th confirmed diagnosis in Malaysia|language=Chinese|work=Sinchew+|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216040505/https://www.sinchew.com.my/pad/con/content_2216462.html|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/wuhan-coronavirus-covid19-malaysia-new-confirmed-case-12430962|title=Malaysia confirms new COVID-19 case related to two others who had tested positive|last=Tjendro|first=Johannes|work=CNA|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=13 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217124307/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/wuhan-coronavirus-covid19-malaysia-new-confirmed-case-12430962|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 February, Malaysia reported two more cases, which are a 27-year-old businessman from Guangzhou and a 32-year-old woman who is from China but resides in Malaysia. The man is warded at Sultanah Bahiyah Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/malaysia-covid-19-coronavirus-new-patients-cases-12438356|title=Malaysia confirms 2 more cases of COVID-19|work=CNA|date=15 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217124454/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/malaysia-covid-19-coronavirus-new-patients-cases-12438356|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A 22nd case subsequently reported within the same day involving an elderly woman from the United States who was among hundreds of passengers who disembarked from the {{MS|Westerdam}} cruise ship in [[Cambodia]] and flew to Kuala Lumpur in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/9b8ab0035389-update1-passenger-from-westerdam-confirmed-by-malaysia-to-have-coronavirus.html|title=Passenger from Westerdam confirmed by Malaysia to have coronavirus|agency=Kyodo News|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216030203/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/9b8ab0035389-update1-passenger-from-westerdam-confirmed-by-malaysia-to-have-coronavirus.html|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The woman is warded at the Sungai Buloh Hospital of Selangor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/two-new-confirmed-covid19-cases-malaysia|title=Three Covid-19 cases confirmed in Malaysia today, bringing total to 22|work=The Edge Markets|date=15 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216035815/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/two-new-confirmed-covid19-cases-malaysia|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Meanwhile, the remaining 143 passengers including a further six passengers from the same flight with the woman had been declared free from the virus and allowed to return into their respective countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-143-penumpang-kapal-persiaran-ms-westerdam-lepas-ujian-saringan-230855|title=COVID-19: 143 penumpang kapal persiaran MS Westerdam lepas ujian saringan|trans-title=COVID-19: 143 passengers aboard MS Westerdam passed screening test|last=Muhamad|first=Hasimi|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217055506/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-143-penumpang-kapal-persiaran-ms-westerdam-lepas-ujian-saringan-230855|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2020/02/656258/6-penumpang-kapal-persiaran-westerdam-disahkan-negatif-covid-19|title=6 penumpang kapal persiaran Westerdam disahkan negatif COVID-19|trans-title=6 Westerdam cruise passengers were negatively diagnosed with COVID-19|last=Yusri Muzamir|first=Muhammad|language=Malay|work=Berita Harian|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217055415/https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2020/02/656258/6-penumpang-kapal-persiaran-westerdam-disahkan-negatif-covid-19|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Holland America Line]] and [[Ministry of Health (Cambodia)|Cambodian health ministry]] requested Malaysia to re-test the US citizen to ensure the accuracy of its findings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50691572/health-ministry-asks-malaysia-to-re-test-specimens-of-us-woman-confirmed-positive-for-coronavirus|title=Health Ministry asks Malaysia to re-test specimens of US woman from MS Westerdam confirmed positive for coronavirus|last=Narim|first=Khuon|work=Khmer Times|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216110208/https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50691572/health-ministry-asks-malaysia-to-re-test-specimens-of-us-woman-confirmed-positive-for-coronavirus|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/16/world/asia/16reuters-china-health-cambodia-cruiseship.html|title=Scramble to Track Cambodia Cruise Ship Passengers After Coronavirus Case Reported|last1=Harris|first1=Ebrahim|last2=Sriring|first2=Orathai|last3=Setboonsarng|first3=Chayut|last4=Johnson|first4=Kay|last5=Feast|first5=Lincoln|agency=Reuters|work=The New York Times|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217074600/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/16/world/asia/16reuters-china-health-cambodia-cruiseship.html|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> This second check-up conducted by the Malaysian health ministry on the woman turned out positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-malaysia/american-woman-from-cruise-ship-tests-positive-again-for-coronavirus-in-malaysia-idUSKBN20A06Q|title=American woman from cruise ship tests positive again for Covid-19 in Malaysia|last1=Tostevin|first1=Matthew|last2=Harris|first2=Ebrahim|last3=Ananthalakshmi|first3=A.|last4=Anantharaman|first4=Muralikumar|agency=Reuters|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/d4cacae28b40-westerdam-passenger-tests-positive-twice-for-virus-malaysia.html|title=Westerdam passenger tests positive twice for virus: Malaysia|agency=Kyodo News|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216135011/https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/d4cacae28b40-westerdam-passenger-tests-positive-twice-for-virus-malaysia.html|archive-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this second test confirmation, the Malaysian authorities announced the remaining passengers of the cruise ships would not be allowed to enter the country despite several flights being chartered by Holland America Line with [[Malaysia Airlines]]. Their departure has not been possible from Cambodia, as this country did not have any direct flights to Europe and the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-16/malaysia-bars-westerdam-passengers-cancels-special-u-s-flights|title=Malaysia Bars Westerdam Cruise Passengers From Entry|last=Ho|first=Yudith|work=Bloomberg|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The woman however discharged soon after she was cleared from the virus after another more check-up.<ref name=\"US woman cleared of COVID-19\"/> This casts doubt from the Cambodian government as well from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) of the United States over the diagnosis conducted by Malaysia despite the Cambodian government still rejected any further speculations that there were already diplomatic tension between Cambodia and Malaysia on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/world/1863174/cambodia-casts-doubt-on-malaysias-virus-diagnosis-of-us-woman|title=Cambodia casts doubt on Malaysia's virus diagnosis of US woman|agency=Kyodo News|work=Bangkok Post|date=22 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200223040324/https://www.bangkokpost.com/world/1863174/cambodia-casts-doubt-on-malaysias-virus-diagnosis-of-us-woman|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50693593/covid-19-no-diplomatic-tension-between-cambodia-and-malaysia-over-the-case-of-83-year-american-woman-found-positive-in-kuala-lumpur|title=COVID-19, No diplomatic tension between Cambodia and Malaysia over the case of 83-year American woman found positive in Kuala Lumpur|work=Fresh News|via=Khmer Times|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200223040116/https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50693593/covid-19-no-diplomatic-tension-between-cambodia-and-malaysia-over-the-case-of-83-year-american-woman-found-positive-in-kuala-lumpur|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health Ministry of Malaysia later released a statement of explanation that the American female patient is only recently recovering after 72 hours of treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/22/health-ministry-explains-american-covid-19-patient-recovering-after-treatme/1839855|title=Health Ministry explains American Covid-19 patient recovering after treatment, after US, Cambodia insist she wasn't infected at all|last=Ar|first=Zurairi|work=The Malay Mail|date=22 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223040751/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/22/health-ministry-explains-american-covid-19-patient-recovering-after-treatme/1839855|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the 15th infected patient involving a Chinese female national had fully recovered, becoming the 8th patient cured from the virus in Malaysia.<ref name=\"one more cured COVID-19\"/> The following day, the first infected Malaysian also reportedly recovered, becoming the 9th cured.<ref name=\"first Malaysian recovered from COVID-19\"/> Another two recovered on 20 February, with only five remained warded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/five-covid-19-patients-are-still-warded-in-hospitals-says-health-minister|title=Malaysia Has Only 5 COVID-2019 Patients Left To Be Treated in Hospitals|last=Razif|first=Sarah|work=Says.com|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223041905/https://says.com/my/news/five-covid-19-patients-are-still-warded-in-hospitals-says-health-minister|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 26 February 20 of the total 22 positive coronavirus patients have been discharged from hospital.<ref name=\"Chinese national Thai border\"/> The same day, a Malaysian female national hospital worker in Sabah's [[Kudat District]] suspected of having contracted the virus were quarantined when she developed symptoms after returning from [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/02/26/kudat-hospital-worker-quarantined/|title=Kudat hospital worker quarantined|work=Borneo Post|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228200225/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/02/26/kudat-hospital-worker-quarantined/|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Although she was later declared free from the virus,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/27/suspected-covid-19-case-in-kudat-turns-out-negative|title=Suspected Covid-19 case in Kudat turns out negative|last=Inus|first=Kristy|work=The Star|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228200924/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/27/suspected-covid-19-case-in-kudat-turns-out-negative|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the Malaysian government had begun to restrict travel from South Korea as precaution measures especially with the large positive reported cases within the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/covid-19-malaysia-imposes-temporary-ban-on-visitors-from-south-korea-IK2059758|title=Covid-19: Malaysia imposes temporary ban on visitors from South Korea|agency=Bernama|via=The Sun|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228201428/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/covid-19-malaysia-imposes-temporary-ban-on-visitors-from-south-korea-IK2059758|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, another two recovered while a new case involving a Malaysian female national who recently returned from [[Japan]] were recorded.<ref name=\"Chinese and American national discharged\"/><ref name=\"Malaysia positive case from Japan\"/><ref name=\"MY-JPN coronavirus\"/> Further two cases involving foreign nationals living in Malaysia; a Japanese female national who works in the capital city of Kuala Lumpur and an Italian male married to a Malaysian spouse were recorded on 28 February.<ref name=\"JPN-ITA coronavirus\"/><ref name=\"JPN-ITA positive COVID-19\"/>\n\n==== Kuala Lumpur religious event ====\nIn March 2020, several Southeast Asian countries experienced a significant rise in cases following a [[Tablighi jamaat]] event held at Jamek Mosque in [[Sri Petaling]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], where many people are believed to have been infected.<ref name=\"NYT mosque\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/17/world/asia/17reuters-health-coronavirus-malaysia-mosque.html|title=How Mass Pilgrimage at Malaysian Mosque Became Coronavirus Hotspot| work=Reuters|via=The New York Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020 }}</ref> The four day event, from 27 February to 1 March, had approximately 16,000 attendees, including about 1,500 from outside Malaysia.<ref name=\"ABC wonder how dangerous\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-19/coronavirus-spread-from-malaysian-event-to-multiple-countries/12066092|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 cases spiked across Asia after a mass gathering in Malaysia. This is how it caught the countries by surprise|last=Barker|first=Anne|work=ABC News|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Attendees shared food, sat close together, and held hands at the event. According to guests, the leaders of the event did not talk about COVID-19 precautions, but most attendees [[Wudu|washed their hands]] during the event.<ref name=\"NYT mosque\"/> Malaysian authorities were criticised for allowing the event to go forward.<ref name=\"NYT mosque\"/>\n\nBy 17 March, almost two thirds of the 673 cases confirmed in Malaysia were related to the event.<ref name=\"NYT mosque\"/><ref name=\"ABC wonder how dangerous\"/> More than 620 people, including those from other countries, who attended the event have tested positive, making it the largest-known centre of transmission in [[South East Asia]]. At least six countries have traced their cases back here &ndash; most of the 73 coronavirus cases in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brunei|Brunei]] have been linked to the event, as well as at least 5 cases in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore|Singapore]], 10 in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Thailand|Thailand]], 22 in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cambodia|Cambodia]], 2 in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Philippines]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/19-filipino-tablighs-positive-for-covid-19-quarantined-in-malaysia/|title=19 Filipino tablighs positive for COVID-19 quarantined in Malaysia|last=Cabrera|first=Ferdinandh B.|work=Minda News|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405085016/https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/19-filipino-tablighs-positive-for-covid-19-quarantined-in-malaysia/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and 2 in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vietnam|Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/another-malaysia-returnee-tests-covid-19-positive-4070591.html|title=Another Malaysia returnee tests Covid-19 positive|last=Le|first=Chi|work=VnExpress|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405085614/https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/another-malaysia-returnee-tests-covid-19-positive-4070591.html|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3076219/coronavirus-i-attended-tabligh-mass-islamic-prayer|title=How the coronavirus spread at Malaysia\u2019s tabligh Islamic gathering|last=Sukumaran|first=Tashny|work=South China Morning Post|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405084542/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3076219/coronavirus-i-attended-tabligh-mass-islamic-prayer|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/world/asia/coronavirus-malaysia-muslims-outbreak.html|title=None of Us Have a Fear of Corona': The Faithful at an Outbreak's Center|last=Beech|first=Hannah|work=The New York Times|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405084052/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/world/asia/coronavirus-malaysia-muslims-outbreak.html|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n{{see also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sabah|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sarawak}}\nFour additional cases, all involving Malaysian nationals, were recorded on 1 March.<ref name=\"four new positive COVID-19 cases\"/><ref name=\"further four positive COVID-19 cases\" /> Seven more cases were reported by the Ministry of Health on 3 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/571344/seven-new-covid-19-cases|title=Seven new Covid-19 cases|last=Rahim|first=Sarah|work=New Straits Times|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> Further 44 new infections were recorded in the early month of March which bringing the total confirmed cases to 99.<ref name=\"further COVID-19 infections in Malaysia\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/malaysias-health-ministry-confirms-28-new-coronavirus-infections-idUSKBN20T1B1|title=Malaysia's health ministry confirms 28 new coronavirus infections|last1=Lee|first1=Liz|last2=Stonestreet|first2=John|agency=Reuters|date=6 March 2020|accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307060213/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/malaysias-health-ministry-confirms-28-new-coronavirus-infections-idUSKBN20T1B1|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 11 March, the Malaysian authorities began to track 5,000 of its citizens believed to have been exposed to the virus in a gathering at a [[Tablighi jamaat]] event in the capital city of Kuala Lumpur which being initiated following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brunei|first positive case]] in neighbouring [[Brunei]] with source of infection from Malaysia.<ref name=\"ABC wonder how dangerous\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/malaysia-tracking-5000-people-possibly-exposed-to-coronavirus-at-religious-event-idUSKBN20Y1I7|title=Malaysia tracking 5,000 people possibly exposed to coronavirus at religious event|last1=Sipalan|first1=Joseph|last2=Richardson|first2=Alex|agency=Reuters|date=11 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312223037/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/malaysia-tracking-5000-people-possibly-exposed-to-coronavirus-at-religious-event-idUSKBN20Y1I7|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many were later confirmed to carrying the virus with all of them have returned into their respective states which subsequently triggering a sporadic case of transmission within local community.<ref name=\"ABC wonder how dangerous\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/twelve-coronavirus-cases-linked-to-malaysian-islamic-conference-idUSKBN20Z0UA|title=Twelve coronavirus cases linked to Malaysian Islamic conference|last1=Latiff|first1=Rozanna|last2=Aravindan|first2=Aradhana|last3=Bandial|first3=Ain|last4=Birsel|first4=Robert|agency=Reuters|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312224420/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/twelve-coronavirus-cases-linked-to-malaysian-islamic-conference-idUSKBN20Z0UA|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysia-confirms-first-sporadic-case-of-coronavirus-indicating-community-spread|title=Malaysia confirms first sporadic case of coronavirus, indicating community spread|work=The Star/Asia News Network|via=The Straits Times|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574102/9-new-covid-19-cases-today|title=9 new Covid-19 cases today|last=Pei Ying|first=Teoh|work=New Straits Times|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314001607/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574102/9-new-covid-19-cases-today|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This raise the total confirmed cases from 158 by 12 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/12/health-ministry-nine-new-covid-19-cases-bringing-total-tally-to-158|title=Health Ministry: Nine new Covid-19 cases, bringing total tally to 158|last=Kaos Jr|first=Joseph|work=The Star|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312133212/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/12/health-ministry-nine-new-covid-19-cases-bringing-total-tally-to-158|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> to 197 by 13 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/covid-19-39-new-cases-reported-on-march-13-bringing-total-to-197|title=Covid-19: 39 new cases reported on March 13; bringing total to 197|last=Cheah|first=Bernard|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313230559/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/covid-19-39-new-cases-reported-on-march-13-bringing-total-to-197|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The correct figures of the gathering participants were later revised by the country Health Ministry from 5,000 to 14,500 which fuelled further estimation that there could be more positive cases to be discovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/moh-reveals-that-over-14-500-malaysians-attended-the-sri-petaling-mosque-tabligh-assembly|title=MOH Reveals That Over 14,500 Malaysians Attended The Sri Petaling Mosque Tabligh Assembly|last=Ram|first=Sadho|work=Says.com|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314032140/https://says.com/my/news/moh-reveals-that-over-14-500-malaysians-attended-the-sri-petaling-mosque-tabligh-assembly|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> From the total of 14,500, 41 of them have been tested positive which increasing the total confirmed cases to 238.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/malaysia-reports-41-new-cases-of-coronavirus-all-linked-to-religious-event-idUSKBN2110H5|title=Malaysia reports 41 new cases of coronavirus, most linked to religious event|last1=Latiff|first1=Rozanna|last2=Bandial|first2=Ain|last3=Ananthalakshmi|first3=A.|last4=Donovan|first4=Kirsten|agency=Reuters|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315034658/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/malaysia-reports-41-new-cases-of-coronavirus-all-linked-to-religious-event-idUSKBN2110H5|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574484/14500-msians-tabligh-gathering-40-test-positive-covid-19|title=14,500 M'sians at 'tabligh' gathering, 40 test positive for Covid-19|last=Arumugam|first=Tharanya|work=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314040506/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574484/14500-msians-tabligh-gathering-40-test-positive-covid-19|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574641/covid-19-41-new-cases-today-total-now-238|title=Covid-19: 41 new cases today; total now 238|last=Naz Harun|first=Hana|work=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315060528/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574641/covid-19-41-new-cases-today-total-now-238|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 15 March 190 new cases, the highest daily cases since the outbreak, has been identified, increasing the confirmed cases to 428.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/covid-19-190-new-cases-recorded-bringing-total-number-to-428|title=Covid-19: 190 new cases recorded, bringing total number to 428|last=Zainal|first=Hanis|work=The Star|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315120006/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/covid-19-190-new-cases-recorded-bringing-total-number-to-428|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This lead the country Health Ministry stating that Malaysia is currently in late containment stage and special meeting will be held to discuss the next course of action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/covid-19-pm-to-hold-special-meeting-over-latest-spike-of-cases-says-health-minister|title=Covid-19: PM to hold special meeting over latest spike of cases, says Health Minister|last=Shah|first=Mohd Farhaan|work=The Star|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316161839/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/15/covid-19-pm-to-hold-special-meeting-over-latest-spike-of-cases-says-health-minister|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n| width  = 24%\n| align  = left\n| quote  = We have a slight chance of deciding the [[COVID-19]] infection network. Help the [[Ministry of Health (Malaysia)|Ministry of Health]] (MOH) with playing your part, as each individual is responsible for taking every step, in the best interests of his or her family. I appeal to all [[Malaysians]], please take this movement control order seriously. Stay home and don't go out. If not, we might face the third wave of the virus, which in turn will be as big as a [[tsunami]], moreover, if we have an unconscious attitude.\n| source = \u2014Malaysia Health Director Noor Hisham message to every Malaysians with the rising number of positive cases reported within the country, 18 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/utama/2020/03/555833/rayuan-kp-kesihatan-kepada-rakyat-malaysia|title=Rayuan KP Kesihatan kepada rakyat Malaysia|trans-title=Appeal of the DG Health to Malaysian citizens|last=Raja Rahim|first=Raja Noraina|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/coronavirus-surges-across-southeast-asia-as-malaysia-warns-of-tsunami-of-cases-idUSKBN21508Q|title=Coronavirus surges across Southeast Asia as Malaysia warns of 'tsunami' of cases|last1=Widianto|first1=Stanley|last2=Harris|first2=Ebrahim|agency=Reuters|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319051802/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-malaysia/coronavirus-surges-across-southeast-asia-as-malaysia-warns-of-tsunami-of-cases-idUSKBN21508Q|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/kl-health-chief-warns-of-tsunami-of-cases-if-curbs-are-flouted|title=KL health chief warns of tsunami of cases if curbs are flouted|last=Leong|first=Trinna|work=The Straits Times|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319051951/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/kl-health-chief-warns-of-tsunami-of-cases-if-curbs-are-flouted|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Only delivery or take-away in Malaysian eateries.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Only take-away and delivery is allowed during the movement control order as seen in this notice released by Malaysia's restaurant outlet of [[Secret Recipe (restaurant)|Secret Recipe]] on 18 March 2020.]]\nOn 16 March, the total confirmed cases had increased to over 553 cases and later that evening, Prime Minister [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] held a live nationwide telecast to inform the decision of the federal government to implement the Movement Control Order.<ref name=\"nationwide control order\"/><ref name=\"Malaysia nationwide control order\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/breaking-malaysia-now-records-428-cases-190-new-people-confirmed-with-covid-19/|title=BREAKING: Malaysia Now Records 428 Cases, 190 New People Confirmed with Covid-19|last=Tai|first=Roxanne|work=World of Buzz|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315130819/https://www.worldofbuzz.com/breaking-malaysia-now-records-428-cases-190-new-people-confirmed-with-covid-19/|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/covid-19-125-new-cases-recorded-bring-total-number-to-553|title=Covid-19: 125 new cases recorded, bringing total number to 553|work=The Star|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316102311/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/covid-19-125-new-cases-recorded-bring-total-number-to-553|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 March, Malaysia reported its first two deaths from the coronavirus, a 60-year-old priest from Emmanuel Baptist Church in [[Kuching]], Sarawak and a 34-year-old participant of the Muslim religious gathering in Sri Petaling from Johor Bahru, [[Johor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/breaking-60-year-old-pastor-in-kuching-is-first-covid-19-death-in-malaysia|title=[BREAKING] Malaysia Records 2 Deaths Caused By COVID-19 Pandemic|last=Vin Ang|first=May|work=Says.com|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317105528/https://says.com/my/news/breaking-60-year-old-pastor-in-kuching-is-first-covid-19-death-in-malaysia|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 673 cases were reported by 17 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/covid-19-120-new-cases-reported-in-malaysia-today-95-related-to-tabligh-gat/1847483|title=Covid-19: 120 new cases reported in Malaysia today, 95 related to tabligh gathering cluster|last=Tee|first=Kenneth|work=Says.com|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319010034/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/covid-19-120-new-cases-reported-in-malaysia-today-95-related-to-tabligh-gat/1847483|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and an additional 117 new cases were diagnosed on 18 March, with 11 discharged, bringing the cumulative statistic for positive and recovered cases to 790 and 60 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-117-new-cases-total-rises-to-790-in-malaysia/|title=Covid-19: 117 new cases, total rises to 790 in Malaysia|work=Bernama|via=Borneo Post|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319010257/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-117-new-cases-total-rises-to-790-in-malaysia/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March, Health Director Noor Hisham once again urged people to stay home, saying that Malaysia has a small chance of blocking the rapid spread of coronavirus disease as compared to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|current situation]] facing by Italy; telling that if it misses the third wave of infection, the situation will be out of control similar to what happened in Italy. It is also very likely that the government will extend the \"movement restriction order\" for another 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2236821.html|title=\u5927\u9a6c\u963b\u65ad\u51a0\u75c5\u8fc5\u901f\u4f20\u64ad\u7387\u5c0f\u00b7\u536b\u751f\u603b\u76d1\uff1a\u653f\u5e9c\u53ef\u80fd\u5ef6\u957f\u7ba1\u5236\u4ee4|trans-title=Malaysia to block rapid spread of crown disease, Health Director: Government may extend control order|language=Chinese|work=Sin Chew Daily|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319010628/https://www.sinchew.com.my/content/content_2236821.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Prime Minister also has similarly appeal to every Malaysians to adhere the control order to prevent further infections within the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/just-stay-home-muhyiddin-appeals-malaysians|title=Just stay at home, Muhyiddin appeals to Malaysians|last=Zainul|first=Emir|work=The Edge Markets|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319020219/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/just-stay-home-muhyiddin-appeals-malaysians|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy 20 March, a total of 1,030 confirmed cases have been reported with another death involving one of the participant of the religious gathering from Sabah; a 58-year-old man.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/576549/malaysias-covid-19-cases-soar-1030|title=Malaysia's Covid-19 cases soar to 1,030|last=Daim|first=Nuradzimmah|work=New Straits Times|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320125738/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/576549/malaysias-covid-19-cases-soar-1030|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149149/tawau-s-first-covid-19-case-dies/|title=Sabah's first Covid-19 case in Tawau dies|work=Daily Express|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320124355/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149149/tawau-s-first-covid-19-case-dies/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, 15 medical staffs treating coronavirus patient in the country have become infected with one placed in [[intensive care unit]] (ICU).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/15-medical-staff-down-with-covid-19-1-in-icu/|title=15 medical staff down with Covid-19, 1 in ICU|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320125336/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/15-medical-staff-down-with-covid-19-1-in-icu/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/fifteen-malaysian-healthcare-workers-infected-with-coronavirus|title=Malaysia records third coronavirus death as cases surge beyond 1,000|work=The Straits Times|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320130852/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/fifteen-malaysian-healthcare-workers-infected-with-coronavirus|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March, another religious gathering participant, a 50-year-old man from [[Malacca]] has died with total infection cases rise to 1,183.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/another-sti-petaling-linked-death-pushes-covid-19-death-to-4/|title=Another Sri Petaling-linked death pushes Covid-19 casualties to 4|last=Agustin|first=Robin|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321091607/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/another-sti-petaling-linked-death-pushes-covid-19-death-to-4/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/576770/malaysia-records-4th-covid-19-death-infections-rise-1183|title=Malaysia records 4th Covid-19 death; infections rise to 1,183|last=Daim|first=Nuradzimmah|work=New Straits Times|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321091624/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/576770/malaysia-records-4th-covid-19-death-infections-rise-1183|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149234/malaysia-records-fourth-fatal-covid-19-case/|title=Malaysia records fourth fatal Covid-19 case|work=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321091822/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149234/malaysia-records-fourth-fatal-covid-19-case/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another four deaths: a 79-year-old woman in Sarawak and her 40-year-old daughter were reported within the day along with a 57-year-old man who has a travel history to [[Vietnam]] before meeting one of the religious gathering participants where he was being hospitalised in Kuala Lumpur and another was a 69-year-old man gathering participant from [[Kelantan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/sarawak-independently-reports-two-more-covid-19-deaths/1848758|title=Sarawak independently reports two more Covid-19 deaths|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321093731/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/sarawak-independently-reports-two-more-covid-19-deaths/1848758|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sinarharian.com.my/article/74884/KHAS/Koronavirus/Malaysia-catat-lima-kematian-baharu-1.74884|title=Malaysia catat lima kematian baharu|trans-title=Malaysia recorded five new deaths|last=Abu Hassan|first=Mohd Ridzuan|language=Malay|work=Sinar Harian|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321111547/https://www.sinarharian.com.my/article/74884/KHAS/Koronavirus/Malaysia-catat-lima-kematian-baharu-1.74884|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/8-m-sians-have-died-from-covid-19-as-dr-noor-hisham-warns-of-a-rise-in-new-cases-next-week|title=8 M'sians Have Died From COVID-19 As Dr Noor Hisham Warns Of A Rise In New Cases Next Week|last=Ram|first=Sadho|work=Says.com|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321114313/https://says.com/my/news/8-m-sians-have-died-from-covid-19-as-dr-noor-hisham-warns-of-a-rise-in-new-cases-next-week|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of six Malaysian police officers also have been infected by the virus while serving their duty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/enam-anggota-pdrm-positif-covid-19-335-anggota-masih-tunggu-keputusan-kpn-234658|title=Enam anggota PDRM positif COVID-19, 335 anggota masih tunggu keputusan|trans-title=Six members of the RMP positive COVID-19, 335 members are still awaiting results - NPC|last=Azman|first=Fareez|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321112510/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/enam-anggota-pdrm-positif-covid-19-335-anggota-masih-tunggu-keputusan-kpn-234658|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Until 23 March, a total of 14 deaths have been recorded involving a 48-year-old doctor from [[Perlis]] who has a travel history to [[Turkey]], a 74-year-old religious gathering participant from [[Penang]] and a 70-year-old [[surau]] chairman from Kuala Lumpur who has a travel history to [[Indonesia]] have died with total infection cases further rise to 1,518.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/doctor-48-becomes-9th-victim-to-succumb-to-covid-19|title=Doctor, 48, becomes 9th victim to succumb to Covid-19|last=Tern Chern|first=Lo|work=The Star|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322054856/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/doctor-48-becomes-9th-victim-to-succumb-to-covid-19|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/covid-19-123-new-cases-reported-deaths-now-at-10|title=Covid-19: 123 new cases reported, deaths now at 10 (March 22)|work=The Star|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322122142/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/covid-19-123-new-cases-reported-deaths-now-at-10|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/23/surau-chairman-70-becomes-11th-victim-to-die-of-covid-19|title=Surau chairman, 70, becomes 11th victim to die of Covid-19|last=Bedi|first=Rashvinjeet S.|work=The Star|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323055610/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/23/surau-chairman-70-becomes-11th-victim-to-die-of-covid-19|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Until 25 March, a total of 72 Malaysia's health workers have been infected by the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149529/covid-19-172-new-cases-19-total-deaths-72-total-health-workers-infected/|title=Covid-19: 172 new cases, 19 total deaths, 72 total health workers infected|work=Daily Express|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326010355/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149529/covid-19-172-new-cases-19-total-deaths-72-total-health-workers-infected/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  On 26 March, the Malaysian royal household confirmed that seven officers from the nation's [[Istana Negara, Jalan Duta|National Palace]] had been confirmed positive, which caused Malaysia's head of state, [[Abdullah of Pahang]] and [[Tunku Azizah Aminah Maimunah Iskandariah|his spouse]] to be put into quarantine, although they themselves had undergone COVID-19 tests with negative results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/news.php?id=1825208|title=King, Queen in self-quarantine after seven staff tested positive for COVID-19|website=Bernama|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, a 62-year-old patient was found to have committed suicide in Serdang Hospital, allegedly due to depression.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578904/suspected-covid-19-patient-commits-suicide-serdang-hospital|title=Suspected Covid-19 patient commits suicide at Serdang Hospital|last=Abdullah|first=Rosyahaida|work=New Straits Times|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405090545/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/578904/suspected-covid-19-patient-commits-suicide-serdang-hospital|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/28/covid-19-pui-found-dead-in-serdang-hospital-toilet-suicide-suspected|title=Covid-19 PUI found dead in Serdang Hospital toilet, suicide suspected (updated)|last=Zolkepli|first=Farik|work=The Star|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405090758/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/28/covid-19-pui-found-dead-in-serdang-hospital-toilet-suicide-suspected|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 March, Malaysia recorded its highest daily fatality cases with seven cases died due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1826376|title=COVID-19: Malaysia records seven deaths, 150 new cases - Health DG|agency=Bernama|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the Director General also informed that the Tabligh cluster had reached the fifth generation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/kluster-jemaah-tabligh-covid-19-memasuki-generasi-kelima-235825|title=Kluster jemaah tabligh COVID-19 memasuki generasi kelima|trans-title=COVID-19 Tabligh cluster entering fifth generation|first=Harits|last=Asyraf Hasnan|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405091306/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/kluster-jemaah-tabligh-covid-19-memasuki-generasi-kelima-235825|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the Health director-general Dr Noor Hisham Abdullah confirmed six new deaths, bringing the total death toll to 43. In addition, 140 new cases were reported, bringing the total number to 2,766.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/six-new-covid-19-deaths-reported-today-total-cases-now-at-2766-DY2199467|title=Six new Covid-19 deaths reported today, total cases now at 2,766|last=Nur|first=Alisha|work=The Sun|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405091600/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/six-new-covid-19-deaths-reported-today-total-cases-now-at-2766-updated-DY2199467|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April, Health Director-General Dr. Noor Hisham Abdullah confirmed that 108 coronavirus patients had recovered. Noor Hisham also confirmed 142 new cases, bringing the total number to 2,908.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/01/covid-19-108-recoveries-recorded-on-wednesday-april-1-highest-in-a-single-day|title=Covid-19: 108 recoveries recorded on Wednesday (April 1), highest in a single day|last=Kaos Jr|first=Joseph|work=The Star|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402092909/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/01/covid-19-108-recoveries-recorded-on-wednesday-april-1-highest-in-a-single-day|archivedate=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 April, he confirmed 208 new cases, taking the total number of the infect to 3,116. In addition, the Health Ministry confirmed that the total number coronavirus deaths was 50.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-208-new-cases-death-toll-now-at-50|title=Covid-19: 208 new cases, death toll now at 50|last=Kaos Jr|first=Joseph|work=The Star|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405124010/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-208-new-cases-death-toll-now-at-50|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 3 April, Dr. Noor Hisham confirmed 217 new cases, taking the total number of cases to 3,333 and three confirmed fatalities, making the total confirmed fatalities 53.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/malaysia-records-3333-confirmed-covid-19-cases-after-217-more-test-positive/|title=Malaysia Records 3,333 Confirmed Covid-19 Cases After 217 More Test Positive|last=Tan|first=Sheralyn|work=World of Buzz|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405125038/https://www.worldofbuzz.com/malaysia-records-3333-confirmed-covid-19-cases-after-217-more-test-positive/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He cited that the sudden spike on new cases were not the 'third wave', but largely due to active case detections on areas affected by [[2020 Malaysia movement control order#Enhanced Movement Control Order|Enhanced Movement Controlled Order]], a stricter version of the MCO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-peningkatan-jumlah-kes-bukan-gelombang-ketiga-kp-kesihatan-236670|title=COVID-19: Peningkatan jumlah kes bukan 'gelombang ketiga' - KP Kesihatan|trans-title=COVID-19: Increase of total cases are not the 'third wave' - Health DG|first=Fareez|last=Azman|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405125346/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-peningkatan-jumlah-kes-bukan-gelombang-ketiga-kp-kesihatan-236670|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Health Ministry confirmed 150 new cases, bringing the total to 3,486. The Ministry also recorded four new deaths, bring the total to 57.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/04/health-ministry-150-new-covid-19-cases-brings-total-to-3486-death-toll-now-at-57|title=Health Ministry: 150 new Covid-19 cases brings total to 3,486, death toll now at 57|last1=Lai|first1=Allison|last2=Tang|first2=Ashley|work=The Star|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404101802/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/04/health-ministry-150-new-covid-19-cases-brings-total-to-3486-death-toll-now-at-57|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 April, Noor Hisham notified that a new cluster had been identified, which involved a person with a travel history to Italy, and now had grew as far as the third generation, with 37 cases and five fatalities as of the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-wujud-kluster-kes-perjalanan-ke-itali-kp-kesihatan-236885|title=COVID-19: Wujud kluster kes perjalanan ke Itali - KP Kesihatan|trans-title=COVID-19: A cluster related to a case with travel history to Italy exists - Health DG|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405130237/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-wujud-kluster-kes-perjalanan-ke-itali-kp-kesihatan-236885|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Preventive measures by government ==\n=== Movement Control Order ===\n{{main|2020 Malaysia movement control order}}\n[[File:Temperature checkup in Kuala Lumpur during movement control.png|thumb|right|Temperature checkup in the capital city of Kuala Lumpur during movement control order.]]\nBeginning from 15 March, Malaysia saw a significant jump in active cases. The Prime Minister of Malaysia held a live nationwide telecast on 16 March 2020 at 10:00PM ([[UTC+8]]) to announce the decision of the federal government in implementing the Movement Control Order. The order was to be in effect from 18 March until 31 March,<ref name=\"nationwide control order\"/><ref name=\"Malaysia nationwide control order\"/> however was extended till 14 April by 25 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_movementorder.php?id=1824718|title=MCO period extended to April 14 - PM|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|website=Bernama}}</ref> Based on the live addressing that evening, six restrictions have been imposed:\n\n# The public is prohibited to mass gather or attend massive events including religious, sports, social and cultural activities. All worshiping locations and business premises should be closed except for supermarkets, public markets, grocery stores and convenience stores that sells everyday necessities. For Muslims, all religious activities in mosques including [[Friday prayer]]s are adjourned in line with decision made on 15 March 2020 by the Special Muzakarah Committee Meeting of the National Fatwa Council.<ref name=\"MCO contents\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575177/covid-19-movement-control-order-imposed-only-essential-sectors-operating|title=Covid-19: Movement Control Order imposed with only essential sectors operating|work=New Straits Times|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316224520/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575177/covid-19-movement-control-order-imposed-only-essential-sectors-operating|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n# Malaysians returning from abroad are required to undergo health check and self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n# Tourists and foreign visitors are restricted to enter the country.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n# Closure of all kindergartens, government and private schools, including daily schools, boarding schools, international schools, tahfiz centres and other primary, secondary and pre-university institutions.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n# Closure of all public and private higher education institution (IPTs) and skill training institutes.<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n# Closure of all government and private premises except for essential services (water, electricity, energy, telecommunications, postal, transportation, irrigation, oil, gas, fuel, lubricants, broadcasting, finance, banking, health, pharmacy, fire, prison, port, airport, safety, defence, cleaning, retail and food supply).<ref name=\"MCO contents\"/>\n\n=== Epidemic prevention for immigration ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer   = Temporary Prohibition released by the State Secretary of the [[Government of Sabah]] and Sarawak Disaster Management Committee of the [[Government of Sarawak]].\n| align    = right\n| width    = 170\n| image1   = Temporary Prohibition in Sabah due to the Coronavirus outbreak, 2020.jpg\n| alt1     = Temporary Prohibition in Sabah\n| caption1 = <center>Prohibition dated 7 February 2020 in Sabah.</center>\n| image2   = Temporary Prohibition in Sarawak due to the Coronavirus outbreak, 2020.jpg\n| alt2     = Temporary Prohibition in Sarawak\n| caption2 = <center>Prohibition dated 1 February 2020 in Sarawak.</center>\n}}\nWith the movement control order put in place since 18 March, all citizens have been prohibited from leaving the country with foreigners also prohibited from entering the country.<ref name=\"Lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysia-to-impose-lockdown-from-wednesday-to-march-31|title=Malaysia bans travel abroad, shuts schools and businesses over coronavirus spread; lockdown till March 31|last=Hassan|first=Hazlin|work=The Straits Times|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324023309/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysia-to-impose-lockdown-from-wednesday-to-march-31|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince the first wave of the virus was reported, [[Thermography|thermal scanners]] were introduced at border points with the Malaysian health authorities placed on high alert.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3046883/china-coronavirus-outbreak-malaysia-high-alert|title=Malaysia on 'high alert' for China coronavirus outbreak|work=South China Morning Post|date=20 January 2020|accessdate=20 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121042347/https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3046883/china-coronavirus-outbreak-malaysia-high-alert|archive-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After the ban on travellers from [[Hubei]] on 27 January, the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]] extended its ban to the Chinese provinces of [[Jiangsu]] and [[Zhejiang]] on 9 February.<ref name=\"three Chinese provinces banned\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/02/09/coronavirus-after-hubei-malaysia-blocks-travellers-from-zhejiang-jiangsu-provinces/|title=Coronavirus: After Hubei, Malaysia blocks travellers from Zhejiang, Jiangsu provinces|agency=Bernama|work=Borneo Post|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217123944/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/02/09/coronavirus-after-hubei-malaysia-blocks-travellers-from-zhejiang-jiangsu-provinces/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state of Sabah expanded their travel restriction to all points of entry by air, sea or land starting 8 February, involving everyone except Sabahan citizens with recent travel history to mainland China within 14 days, while Sabahan citizens with such travel history must undergo a 14-day quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news_coronavirus.php?id=1812373|title=Coronavirus: Sabah expands travel restrictions effective tomorrow|agency=Bernama|date=7 February 2020|accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> The state of Sarawak closed its borders to all Chinese visitors with immediate effect on 1 February, except for people with employment passes, student passes or long-term social visit passes. However, those visitors were required to undergo self-quarantine at home for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1810809|title=Sarawak bars visitors with recent travel history to China|agency=Bernama|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> With the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|increasing cases]] in South Korea, both Sabah and Sarawak government began to extended its travel restrictions into the country from 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147905/sabah-extends-covid-19-travel-restrictions-to-s-korea/|title=Sabah extends Covid-19 travel restrictions to S Korea|work=Daily Express|date=29 February 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314062724/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147905/sabah-extends-covid-19-travel-restrictions-to-s-korea/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/01/foreigners-who-have-been-to-s-korea-in-last-fortnight-banned/|title=Foreigners who have been to S. Korea in last fortnight banned|work=The Borneo Post|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063044/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/01/foreigners-who-have-been-to-s-korea-in-last-fortnight-banned/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 4 March, Sarawak further added [[Italy]] and [[Iran]] into its travel restrictions list.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/04/s039wak-bans-italian-and-iranian-travellers-after-china-and-south-korea|title=S'wak bans Italian and Iranian travellers, after China and South Korea|last=Ling|first=Sharon|work=The Star|date=4 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063646/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/04/s039wak-bans-italian-and-iranian-travellers-after-china-and-south-korea|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Malaysia added seven regions towards its travel restriction list, which include [[Lombardy]], [[Veneto]] and [[Emilia-Romagna]] in Italy; [[Hokkaido]] in Japan; and [[Tehran]], [[Qom Province|Qom]] and [[Gilan Province|Gilan]] in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/05/seven-provinces-in-italy-japan-and-iran-added-to-malaysia039s-covid-19-travel-ban-list|title=Seven provinces in Italy, Japan, and Iran added to Malaysia's Covid-19 travel ban list|last=Kaos Jr|first=Joseph|work=The Star|date=5 March 2020|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> By 10 March, Sabah also began to added Italy and Iran into its restrictions list.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/sabah-bans-travellers-from-iran-and-italy|title=Sabah bans travellers from Iran and Italy|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=10 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314064405/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/sabah-bans-travellers-from-iran-and-italy|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 March, Malaysia announced a full restriction on foreign nationals directly from Italy, Iran and South Korea starting from 13 March, while Malaysians from those countries will be quarantined for 14 days.<ref name=\"bars travellers from three countries\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/573741/covid-19-malaysia-bars-travellers-italy-iran-and-south-korea|title=Covid-19: Malaysia bars travellers from Italy, Iran and South Korea|work=New Straits Times|date=11 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312221527/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/573741/covid-19-malaysia-bars-travellers-italy-iran-and-south-korea|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark#March lockdown|13 March Denmark lockdown]], Malaysia has added the country into its travel ban list effective from 14 March.<ref name=\"Denmark travel ban\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574096/travel-ban-denmark-saturday|title=Travel ban on Denmark from Saturday|last=Pei Ying|first=Teoh|work=New Straits Times|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314040937/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574096/travel-ban-denmark-saturday|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Overseas travel alert and quarantine arrangements ===\nThe following are warnings and quarantine arrangements for inbound and outbound travel:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Alert level\n! Country\n! Date of issue\n! Cancellation date\n! Note\n|-\n| Prohibit\n| {{flagu|China}}\n| {{nowrap|9 February 2020}}\n| {{green|In force}}\n| In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Mainland China]], the government announced that travellers from the three Chinese provinces of [[Hubei]], [[Jiangsu]] and [[Zhejiang]] are banned with immediate effect from 9 February.<ref name=\"three Chinese provinces banned\"/>\n|-\n| Prohibit\n| {{flagu|Iran}}<br />{{flagu|Italy}}<br />{{nowrap|{{flagu|South Korea}}}}\n| {{nowrap|13 March 2020}}\n| {{green|In force}}\n| In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], the government announced that all Malaysian citizens, permanent residents and people with long-term residence permits from that date must be self-quarantine at their homes for 14 days after returning from the three countries.<ref name=\"bars travellers from three countries\"/>\n|-\n| Prohibit\n| {{flagu|Denmark}}\n| {{nowrap|14 March 2020}}\n| {{green|In force}}\n| In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark|Denmark]] and its recent [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark#Lockdown|lockdown]], the government announced a travel ban to the country.<ref name=\"Denmark travel ban\"/>\n|-\n| Prohibit\n| All countries\n| {{nowrap|18 March 2020}}\n| {{green|In force}}\n| With the movement control order put in place since 18 March, all citizens have been prohibited from leaving the country with foreigners also prohibited from entering the country.<ref name=\"Lockdown\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Testing and treatment centre ===\n[[File:Machang Bubuk voluntary fire brigade disinfection work during MCO (49682305433).jpg|thumb|right|A voluntary [[Fire and Rescue Department of Malaysia|Malaysia's fire brigade]] during [[disinfection]] works in [[Machang Bubok]] Wet Market, [[Seberang Perai]], 21 March 2020.]]\nOn 5 January, the National Crisis Preparedness and Response Centre (CPRC) under the Ministry of Health Malaysia started to operate.<ref name=\"hospitals\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chinapress.com.my/20200203/%E2%97%A4%E6%AD%A6%E6%B1%89%E8%82%BA%E7%82%8E%E2%97%A2-%E5%8D%AB%E9%95%BF%EF%BC%9A%E6%92%A4%E4%BE%A8%E8%A1%8C%E5%8A%A8%E4%B8%A5%E8%B0%A8-%E7%96%91%E6%84%9F%E6%9F%93%E8%80%85%E7%BB%AD%E7%95%99%E6%AD%A6/|title=\u25e4\u6b66\u6c49\u80ba\u708e\u25e2 \u536b\u957f\uff1a\u64a4\u4fa8\u884c\u52a8\u4e25\u8c28 \u7591\u611f\u67d3\u8005\u7eed\u7559\u6b66\u6c49|trans-title=\u25e4Wuhan Pneumonia\u25e2 Chief of Health: Rigorous withdrawal of overseas Chinese|language=Chinese|work=China Press|date=3 February 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> There are 57 hospitals that provide screening services for coronavirus,<ref name=hospitals/> while among them, 26 government hospitals are responsible for the confirmation of coronavirus and the suspected patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/27/coronavirus-health-ministry-identifies-26-hospitals-nationwide-to-handle-cases|title=Coronavirus: Health Ministry identifies 26 hospitals nationwide to handle suspected cases|work=Bernama|via=The Star|date=27 January 2020|accessdate=7 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205050057/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/27/coronavirus-health-ministry-identifies-26-hospitals-nationwide-to-handle-cases|archive-date=5 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orientaldaily.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/28/324373|title=\u3010\u6b66\u6c49\u80ba\u708e\u75ab\u60c5\u3011\u5168\u9a6c26\u533b\u9662\u3000\u5904\u7406\u7591\u4f3c\u4e0e\u786e\u8bca\u75c5\u4f8b|trans-title=[Wuhan pneumonia epidemic situation] 26 hospitals in Malaysia deal with suspected and confirmed cases|work=Oriental Daily|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322043840/https://www.orientaldaily.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/28/324373|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith the rapid increase of infections, a further total of 409 sites across the country have been gazetted by the federal government as quarantine zones for coronavirus patients comprising public universities, community colleges, technical institutes, former [[National Service Training Programme (Malaysia)|National Service]] (PLKN) camps, training centres, polytechnics and hotels owned by federal ministries, departments, agencies and statutory bodies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/putrajaya-gazettes-409-facilities-as-covid-19-quarantine-stations/1848820|title=Putrajaya gazettes 409 facilities as Covid-19 quarantine stations|last=Ong|first=Justin|work=The Malay Mail|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322044523/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/putrajaya-gazettes-409-facilities-as-covid-19-quarantine-stations/1848820|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Repatriation of Malaysian nationals abroad ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! colspan=4| Record Form of Repatriation for Malaysian non-main officials abroad\n|-\n! Departure date\n! Number of passengers\n! Departure airport\n! Arrival airport\n|-\n| 4 February 2020\n| 107<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chinapress.com.my/20200204/\u25e4\u6b66\u6c49\u80ba\u708e\u25e2\u5230\u5bb6\u4e86\uff01-\u6b66\u6c49\u64a4\u4fa8\u4e13\u673a\u62b5klia2/|title=\u25e4\u6b66\u6c49\u80ba\u708e\u25e2\u6b66\u6c49\u56de\u6765\u5927\u9a6c\u4eba \u8fd9\u91cc\u9694\u79bb|trans-title=\u25e4Wuhan pneumonia\u25e2Wuhan returnees to Malaysia to be isolated here|language=Chinese|work=China Press|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n| [[Wuhan Tianhe International Airport|Wuhan \u2013 Tianhe]]\n| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|KL \u2013 Sepang]]\n|-\n| 26 February 2020\n| 66<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/02/548533/66-rakyat-malaysia-tiba-dari-wuhan-metrotv|title=66 rakyat Malaysia tiba dari Wuhan [METROTV]|trans-title=66 Malaysian citizens arrive from Wuhan [METROTV]|language=Malay|work=Bernama|via=Harian Metro|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| [[Wuhan Tianhe International Airport|Wuhan \u2013 Tianhe]]\n| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|KL \u2013 Sepang]]\n|-\n| 21 March 2020\n| 212<ref name=\"MY-UZ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/576992/212-malaysians-arrive-safely-home-tashkent|title=212 Malaysians arrive safely home from Tashkent|last=Athira Yusof|first=Teh|work=New Straits Times|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323073921/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/576992/212-malaysians-arrive-safely-home-tashkent|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| [[Islam Karimov Tashkent International Airport|Tashkent \u2013 Islam Karimov]]\n| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|KL \u2013 Sepang]]\n|-\n| 22 March 2020\n| 55 (comprising 46 [[Malaysians]], eight [[Singaporeans]] and one [[Indonesians|Indonesian]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/rina-harun-55-individuals-returning-to-malaysia-sunday-march-21|title=Rina Harun: 55 individuals returning to Malaysia from Iran on Sunday (March 22)|work=Bernama|via=The Star|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322003512/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/rina-harun-55-individuals-returning-to-malaysia-sunday-march-21|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| [[Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport|Tehran \u2013 Imam Khomeini]]\n| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|KL \u2013 Sepang]]\n|-\n| 30 March 2020\n| 179 Malaysians<ref name=\"stranded Malaysians 31 March\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/more-than-4300-m-sians-still-stranded-overseas-says-deputy-minister-YY2199427|title=More than 4,300 M\u2019sians still stranded overseas, says deputy minister|last=Mohsen|first=Amar|work=The Sun|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405164615/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/more-than-4300-m-sians-still-stranded-overseas-says-deputy-minister-YY2199427|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| [[Amritsar]], India<ref name=\"Stranded Malaysians 31 March\"/>\n| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|KL \u2013 Sepang]]\n|-\n| 31 March 2020\n| 144 Malaysians<ref name=\"stranded Malaysians 31 March\"/>\n| Myanmar<ref name=\"stranded Malaysians 31 March\"/>\n| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|KL \u2013 Sepang]]\n|}\n\nThe Malaysian government has made the repatriation of its citizens abroad a priority; beginning with the first repatriations from China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/02/more-govt-officials-off-to-wuhan-to-bring-back-malaysians|title=More govt officials off to Wuhan to bring back Malaysians|last=Muthiah|first=Wani|work=The Star|date=2 February 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318021500/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/02/more-govt-officials-off-to-wuhan-to-bring-back-malaysians|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> During the first repatriation, two persons were found to be infected with the virus and were subsequently quarantined and treated in the country until they have fully recovered.<ref name=\"father and son recovered and discharged from hospital\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/world/two-malaysians-brought-back-china-tested-positive-coronavirus-minister|title=Two Malaysians brought back from China tested positive for coronavirus: Minister|work=Today|date=2 February 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200318021748/https://www.todayonline.com/world/two-malaysians-brought-back-china-tested-positive-coronavirus-minister|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a total of 212 Malaysians arrived from [[Uzbekistan]] through a flight sponsored by the [[Government of Uzbekistan|Uzbekistan government]] which is also being used to repatriated Uzbek citizens in Malaysia.<ref name=\"MY-UZ\"/> On that same day, 372 Malaysians departed [[Tamil Nadu]] on two chartered flights. On 22 March, it was reported that the Malaysian government was waiting for the [[Government of India|Indian government]]'s permission to organise six more flights to evacuate Malaysians still in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/22/covid-19-more-special-flights-planned-to-evacuate-malaysians-from-india/1849029|title=Covid-19: More special flights planned to evacuate Malaysians from India|work=Bernama|via=The Malay Mail|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323100642/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/22/covid-19-more-special-flights-planned-to-evacuate-malaysians-from-india/1849029|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the [[Minister of Defence (Malaysia)|Defence Minister]] Datuk Seri [[Ismail Sabri Yaakob]] announced that all Malaysians returning from overseas would have to undergo a compulsory two-week quarantine at designated quarantine centres around the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/14-day-compulsory-quarantine-for-malaysians-returning-from-overseas-BY2199120|title=14-day compulsory quarantine for Malaysians returning from overseas|last=Nur|first=Alisha|work=The Sun|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405165342/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/14-day-compulsory-quarantine-for-malaysians-returning-from-overseas-BY2199120|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> That same day, Deputy Foreign Minister [[Kamaruddin Jaffar]] confirmed that 4,374 Malaysians were stranded abroad due to the travel restrictions and delays created by the global coronavius pandemic. This figure only consists of Malaysians who had bought return tickets but were unable to return due to travel restrictions. According to Kamaruddin, 2,156 Malaysians are stranded in India, 680 in Indonesia, 337 in Thailand, 226 in Australia, 153 in New Zealand, 128 in Pakistan, and 121 in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"stranded Malaysians 31 March\"/>\n\nOn 5 April, the [[Johor]] Immigration Department announced that Malaysians with Singaporean work permits would be required to take swab tests in Singaporean clinics and hospitals to show that they are free of the coronavirus in order to return to Johor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/m-sians-with-s-pore-work-permits-must-do-covid-19-test-before-returning-to-johor-NA2211924|title=M\u2019sians with S\u2019pore work permits must do Covid-19 test before returning to Johor|work=The Sun|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200405023315/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/m-sians-with-s-pore-work-permits-must-do-covid-19-test-before-returning-to-johor-NA2211924|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> That same day, Deputy Foreign Minister Kamaruddin announced that the Government had brought back 4,811 stranded Malaysians from affected countries. He also upgraded the number of Malaysians stranded abroad to 2,298: 1,016 in India, 172 in Thailand, 136 in New Zealand, 128 in Pakistan, 122 in Vietnam, 83 in Saudi Arabia, 77 in Australia, 66 in the Philippines, 65 in Sri Lanka, and 43 in Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/covid-19-2298-malaysians-still-stranded-in-47-countries-MA2211952|title=Covid-19: 2,298 Malaysians still stranded in 47 countries|work=The Sun|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200405023734/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/covid-19-2298-malaysians-still-stranded-in-47-countries-MA2211952|archivedate=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Bans on mass gathering events ===\nImmediately after the spikes of the cases which related to the [[Sri Petaling]] [[Tabligh Jamaat|Tabligh event]], [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]] [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] announces that all events that involving mass gathering in any genre including international, religious, sports, meetups and social must be cancelled or postponed until 30 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/pm-mass-gatherings-including-religious-events-to-be-cancelled-or-postponed/1846319|title=PM: Mass gatherings, including religious events, to be cancelled or postponed until April 30|last=Dzulkifly|first=Danial|work=The Malay Mail|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314073743/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/pm-mass-gatherings-including-religious-events-to-be-cancelled-or-postponed/1846319|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/muhyiddin-all-gatherings-postponed-until-april-30-or-to-be-cancelled-due-to-covid-19|title=Muhyiddin: All gatherings postponed until April 30 or to be cancelled due to Covid-19|last=Sivanandam|first=Hemananthani|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316104004/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/muhyiddin-all-gatherings-postponed-until-april-30-or-to-be-cancelled-due-to-covid-19|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the end date for the ban on mass gathering events are subject to revision depending on the situation of the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574433/govt-decides-cancellation-postponement-all-mass-gatherings|title=Govt decides on cancellation, postponement of all mass gatherings|last1=Abas|first1=Azura|last2=Othman|first2=Ahmad Fairuz|work=New Straits Times|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316104652/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574433/govt-decides-cancellation-postponement-all-mass-gatherings|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, Registrar of Societies (RoS) bans all [[List of political parties in Malaysia|parties registered with RoS]] from organising any meeting and activities until 30 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/covid-19-ros-bans-all-activities-by-societies|title=Covid-19: RoS bans all activities by societies|last=S. Bedi|first=Rashvinjeet|work=The Star|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316105018/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/16/covid-19-ros-bans-all-activities-by-societies|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspension of extracurricular activity in schools ===\nThe [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] of Malaysia announces that all [[extracurricular activity]] in schools will be suspended starting from March 2020 until further notice.<ref name=\"sports and co-curricular activities in schools postponed\">{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/moe-all-sports-and-co-curricular-activities-in-march-to-be-postponed-due-to-covid-19|title=MOE: All Sports And Co-Curricular Activities To Be Postponed Due To COVID-19|last=Rozaidee|first=Arisha|work=Says.com|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314032901/https://says.com/my/news/moe-all-sports-and-co-curricular-activities-in-march-to-be-postponed-due-to-covid-19|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soyacincau.com/2020/03/13/covid-19-malaysia-postpone-cancel-all-events-gathering-30-april/|title=Malaysia Govt: Postpone or cancel all gatherings and events until 30 April|last=Wong|first=Alexander|work=SoyaCincau|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316103252/https://www.soyacincau.com/2020/03/13/covid-19-malaysia-postpone-cancel-all-events-gathering-30-april/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Economic stimulus plan===\nOn 27 March, Prime Minister [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] launched an economic stimulus package known as the \"caring package\" worth RM250 billion. Of these, RM128 billion was used to protect the welfare of the people and RM100 billion to support businesses, including small and medium enterprises (SMEs).\n\nThe government also announced a RM600 million allocation on March 23 to the Ministry of Health for the purchase of equipment and to hire contract personnel, especially nurses. It has also announced that contributors of the [[Employees Provident Fund (Malaysia)|Employees Provident Fund]] can withdraw  up to RM500 per month for 12 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/covid-19-pencarum-kwsp-dibenar-keluar-rm500-sebulan-bermula-1-april-234864|title=COVID-19: Pencarum KWSP dibenar keluar RM500 sebulan bermula 1 April|first=Firdaus|last=Azli|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|website=Astro Awani|language=ms}}</ref>\n\nAn allocation of RM130 million has also been announced and will be distributed equally to all states to help overcome the Covid-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/27/muhyiddin-unveils-rm250bil-economic-stimulus-package|title=Muhyiddin unveils RM250bil economic stimulus package &#124; The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my}}</ref> The details of the plan are:\n\n# Budget of RM500 million to the Ministry of Health to enhance the health and resources of the ministry.\n# The government raises special allowances for healthcare workers from RM400 to RM600 a month from April 1 until the end of the pandemic.\n# Additional special allowance of RM200 per month for frontliner for police, immigration, Customs Department, [[Malaysian Civil Defence Force]] and [[RELA Corps]] personels.\n# Aid of RM1,600 to households earning less than RM4,000, with RM1,000 paid in April and RM600 in May.\n# National Concerns fund with RM10 billion worth of cash payments will be provided to groups B40 and M40, including private workers, farmers and fishermen. These include RM1,600 to four million households earning RM4,000 and below; RM1,000 for households earning RM4,000 above; RM800 for Malaysians aged 21 and over who earn RM2,000 and below; RM500 for Malaysians aged 21 and over earns between RM2,000 and RM4,000.\n# RM200 of one-time assistance to affected higher education institution students.\n# Free internet from April onwards until the end of the MCO.\n# The joint government of TNB will increase the allocation of RM530 million for a discount of between 15% and 50% for electricity usage up to 600&nbsp;kW per month for six months from the April bill.\n# Exemption of rent for ''Program Perumahan Rakyat'' and public housing for six months.\n# Insurance and takaful companies set aside RM8 million to cover COVID-19 inspection costs up to RM300 per policyholder.\n# Government to provide a payment of RM500 to approximately 120,000 e-hailing drivers starting April 1.\n# The Government and [[Bank Negara Malaysia]] will set aside an additional allocation of RM4.5 billion for SMEs and micro-entrepreneurs which will consist of five initiatives.\n# One-off RM500 aid for 120,000 e-hailing drivers nationwide with an allocation of RM60 million. This is in addition to the one-time assistance announced for taxi drivers announced in the previous stimulus package.\n# The government will pay the salaries incurred by contractors involved in the service sector, such as cleaning services and food supplies cooked at government agencies.\n# The government will introduce a subsidy of RM600 a month for three months for employers with a 50% reduction since Jan 1, for workers with less than RM4,000 in salaries.\n# The government will continue all projects allocated in the 2020 Budget, including [[East Coast Rail Line|ECRL]], [[Sungai Buloh\u2013Serdang\u2013Putrajaya line|MRT2]] and the National Sustainability and Sustainability Plan (NFCP) in line with its focus on ensuring sustainable economic development.\n# Human Resources Development Fund (HRDF) is tax-exempted for all sectors for six months beginning April 2020.\n# Federal government premises such as school cafeteria, nursery, cafeteria and convenience store are exempt from rent for six months.\n# Government pensioners to receive RM500 cash assistance.\n\n== Implications ==\n=== Economy, trade and tourism ===\n{{Quote box\n| width  = 24%\n| align  = right\n| quote  = I think it's very contained right now and there's ... no cause for panic at all, but we cannot be complacent about this and we'll continue to be on serious alert.\n| source = \u2014Malaysia Health Minister [[Dzulkefly Ahmad]] during conversation with [[CNBC]] on the situation of the outbreak in Malaysia, 19 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/coronavirus-spread-in-malaysia-is-no-cause-for-panic-health-minister.html|title=Coronavirus spread in Malaysia is 'no cause for panic,' health minister says|last=Nee Lee|first=Yen|work=CNBC|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n}}\nStocks on Malaysia's [[stock exchange]] of [[Bursa Malaysia]] tumbled during the outbreak as investors sold securities due to the expected economic impact caused by the virus,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2020/01/29/coronavirus-fears-hit-bursa-malaysia|title=Coronavirus fears hit Bursa Malaysia|last=Aruna|first=P.|work=The Star|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223024423/https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2020/01/29/coronavirus-fears-hit-bursa-malaysia|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which along with other emerging [[stock market]]s are predicted to remain until June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2020/01/561032/coronavirus-may-bug-bursa-other-emerging-markets|title=Coronavirus may bug Bursa, other emerging markets|last=Yusof|first=Ayisy|work=New Straits Times|date=30 January 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223024234/https://www.nst.com.my/business/2020/01/561032/coronavirus-may-bug-bursa-other-emerging-markets|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> With China as Malaysia's largest trading partner, the [[Economy of Malaysia|country's economy]] was directly impacted and economic experts have warned the prolonged virus outbreak could hit the country gross domestic product (GDP) hard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/02/20/prolonged-covid-19-may-hit-malaysias-gdp-hard/|title=Prolonged Covid-19 may hit Malaysia's GDP hard|last1=Zainuddin|first1=Alifah|last2=Shaharuddin|first2=Hussein|work=The Malaysian Reserve|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221191637/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/02/20/prolonged-covid-19-may-hit-malaysias-gdp-hard/|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Malaysia which also largely relied on [[tourism]] and being among the top destinations for Chinese tourists, suffered a stark decline of tourist arrival from [[Mainland China]] due to the outbreak with the [[tourism in Malaysia|tourism industry]] hit hardest; costing around [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]]3.37 billion losses until March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201902/28/WS5c775560a3106c65c34ebf06.html|title=Malaysia attracts 2.9 mln Chinese tourists in 2018|agency=Xinhua News Agency|via=China Daily|date=28 February 2019|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219114650/https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201902/28/WS5c775560a3106c65c34ebf06.html|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/tourismlinked-stocks-hit-hard-wuhan-virus|title=Tourism-linked stocks hit hard by Wuhan virus|last=Xue Ying|first=Tan|work=The Edge Markets|date=3 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222025306/https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/tourismlinked-stocks-hit-hard-wuhan-virus|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-strikes-tourism-factories-consumption-around|title=Coronavirus Strikes Tourism, Factories, Consumption around Southeast Asia|last=Jennings|first=Ralph|publisher=Voice of America|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222025746/https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-strikes-tourism-factories-consumption-around|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://time.com/5783505/thailand-asia-tourism-covid-19-china-coronavirus/|title='It Will Be Catastrophic.' Asia's Tourism-Dependent Economies Are Being Hit Hard by the Coronavirus|last=Campbell|first=Charlie|work=Time|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/muhyiddin-tourism-industry-hit-hard-by-covid-19-to-lose-rm3.37b-while-gdp-s/1846323|title=Muhyiddin: Tourism industry hit hardest by Covid-19, faces RM3.37b loss|last=Dzulkifly|first=Danial|work=The Malay Mail|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314071918/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/muhyiddin-tourism-industry-hit-hard-by-covid-19-to-lose-rm3.37b-while-gdp-s/1846323|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Malaysian states highly dependent on tourism sectors and being the point for Mainland Chinese visitors such as [[Johor]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/566293/johor-tourism-sector-suffers-severe-covid-19-fallout-seeks-govt-help|title=Johor tourism sector suffers severe Covid-19 fallout, seeks govt help|last=D'Silva|first=Vincent|work=New Straits Times|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222031739/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/566293/johor-tourism-sector-suffers-severe-covid-19-fallout-seeks-govt-help|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Malacca]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/02/14/melakas-tourist-footfall-drops-thousands-of-bookings-cancelled/|title=Melaka's tourist footfall drops, thousands of bookings cancelled|last1=Aziz|first1=Afiq|last2=Naharul|first2=Muhd Amin|work=The Malaysian Reserve|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222031140/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/02/14/melakas-tourist-footfall-drops-thousands-of-bookings-cancelled/|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Penang]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/11/penang-tourism-feeling-the-effects|title=Penang tourism feeling the effects|last=Sekaran|first=R.|work=The Star|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222030524/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/11/penang-tourism-feeling-the-effects|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Sabah]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elevenmyanmar.com/news/sabah-tourism-players-brace-for-zero-chinese-tourist-arrivals-ask-govt-to-help-through-bad|title=Sabah tourism players brace for 'zero' Chinese tourist arrivals, ask govt to help through bad patch|work=Eleven Myanmar|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222030759/https://elevenmyanmar.com/news/sabah-tourism-players-brace-for-zero-chinese-tourist-arrivals-ask-govt-to-help-through-bad|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> were among the heaviest affected with hotel bookings and food stalls have reported large loss in businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3051381/coronavirus-food-stalls-durian-sellers-malaysia-hit-hard|title=Coronavirus: food stalls, durian sellers in Malaysia hit hard as Chinese tourists stay away|work=Star Digital|via=South China Morning Post|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147560/hotel-room-cancellations-result-in-rm66m-losses/|title=Hotel room cancellations result in RM66m losses|agency=Bernama|via=Daily Express|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222032705/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147560/hotel-room-cancellations-result-in-rm66m-losses/|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> These subsequently forced the states to shift their focus to the Southeast Asian market due to the decline of Mainland Chinese tourists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/13/covid-19-malaysia-eyeing-asean-market-due-to-shortfall-of-chinese-tourists|title=Covid-19: Malaysia eyeing Asean market due to shortfall of Chinese tourists|last=S. Bedi|first=Rashvinjeet|work=The Star|date=13 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222032705/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/147560/hotel-room-cancellations-result-in-rm66m-losses/|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-malaysia-domestic-tourism-selangor-johor-sabah-12392866|title=Malaysian states to consider pivot towards domestic tourism amid COVID-19 outbreak|last=Kanyakumari|first=D|work=CNA|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222034857/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/coronavirus-malaysia-domestic-tourism-selangor-johor-sabah-12392866|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Regardless the large losses incurred by tourism businesses, a number of Malaysians have voiced their concerns over the spread of the virus and urging a ban on travellers from China to the country with some 149,000 in support of the call.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/559942/some-malaysians-calling-ban-chinese-tourists|title=Some Malaysians calling for ban on Chinese tourists|last=Solhi|first=Farah|work=New Straits Times|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223034603/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/559942/some-malaysians-calling-ban-chinese-tourists|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/26/over-100000-people-petition-to-block-chinese-nationals-from-entering-malays/1831531|title=Over 100,000 people petition to block Chinese nationals from entering Malaysia, following coronavirus outbreak|last=Dzulkifly|first=Danial|work=The Malay Mail|date=26 January 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223034817/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/26/over-100000-people-petition-to-block-chinese-nationals-from-entering-malays/1831531|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Aberdeen Standard Investments of Malaysia also predicted the country currency of [[Malaysian ringgit]] (MYR) to weaken further throughout the local and worldwide outbreak which exacerbate further by instable local political scene in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/26/malaysia-ringgit-myr-to-weaken-amid-political-chaos-coronavirus-aberdeen.html|title=Malaysian ringgit set to weaken further as political chaos and coronavirus take hold, says Aberdeen|last1=Huang|first1=Eustance|last2=Nee Lee|first2=Yen|work=CNBC|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228122508/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/26/malaysia-ringgit-myr-to-weaken-amid-political-chaos-coronavirus-aberdeen.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Panic buying and essential item shortages ===\n{{multiple image\n| footer        = The aftermath of [[panic buying]] as seen in a Malaysian [[supermarket]] on 18 March 2020.\n| align         = left\n| caption_align = center\n| image1        = Panic Buying in AEON Mall Malaysia.png\n| width1        = 195\n| caption1      = Panic buying in one of the [[AEON (company)|AEON]] malls in the country.\n| image2        = Toilet papers in Malaysia out of stock.png\n| width2        = 195\n| caption2      = The [[toilet paper]] section, cleared of stock.\n}}\n[[File:All masks sold out in Taman Wahyu, Kuala Lumpur.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Face masks out of stock notice in a [[Watsons]] outlet within Malaysia's capital of [[Kuala Lumpur]].]]\nThe increase in cases and public awareness on the threat posed by the virus has exacerbated [[panic buying]] of [[surgical masks]] and [[hand sanitiser]]s which were [[:wikt:sell like hot cakes|selling like hot cakes]] within a short period. Malaysian cities, such as [[Johor Bahru]] and [[Kota Kinabalu]], have reported shortages on surgical masks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/01/28/face-masks-hand-sanitiser-sold-out-in-jb-kk/|title=Face masks, hand sanitiser sold out in JB, KK|agency=Bernama|via=The Malaysian Reserve|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223030553/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/01/28/face-masks-hand-sanitiser-sold-out-in-jb-kk/|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while a cleaning company in [[Shah Alam]] reported a higher demand for hand sanitisers due to the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/leisure/2020/02/18/deadly-covid-19-outbreak-triples-demand-for-hand-sanitisers/|title=Deadly Covid-19 outbreak triples demand for hand sanitisers|last=Wong|first=Noel|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=18 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223030812/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/leisure/2020/02/18/deadly-covid-19-outbreak-triples-demand-for-hand-sanitisers/|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There were reports that some pharmacies and traders have been selling masks with higher prices than the controlled price set by the [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry of Malaysia]] which can lead to fines of up to RM10,000 ([[United States dollar|US$]]2,387).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/14/shop-gets-rm10000-fine-for-selling-face-masks-above-maximum-price/1837402|title=Shop gets RM10,000 fine for selling face masks above maximum price|agency=Bernama|work=The Malay Mail|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223032538/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/14/shop-gets-rm10000-fine-for-selling-face-masks-above-maximum-price/1837402|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/19/pharmacy-fined-rm10000-for-selling-face-masks-above-controlled-price/1839018|title=Pharmacy fined RM10,000 for selling face masks above controlled price|agency=Bernama|work=The Malay Mail|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223032256/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/19/pharmacy-fined-rm10000-for-selling-face-masks-above-controlled-price/1839018|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This also includes reports of some people being scammed by unscrupulous individuals taking advantage of the pandemic situation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-businessman-loses-s89000-in-scam-in-bid-to-buy-face-masks|title=Coronavirus: Businessman in Malaysia loses S$89,000 to scammer in bid to buy face masks|work=The Star/Asia News Network|via=The Straits Times|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314021157/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-businessman-loses-s89000-in-scam-in-bid-to-buy-face-masks|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/scammed-for-face-masks|title=Scammed for face masks|last=Chung|first=Clarissa|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314021533/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/scammed-for-face-masks|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the increasing shortages of masks in the country with both pharmacies and suppliers struggling to meet the increasing demands,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/malaysia/struggle-meet-demand-masks-malaysia|title=Struggle to meet demand for masks in Malaysia|work=The Star/Asia News Network|via=AsiaOne|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223033554/https://www.asiaone.com/malaysia/struggle-meet-demand-masks-malaysia|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-malaysian-pharmacists-and-suppliers-struggle-to-meet-demand-for-masks|title=Coronavirus: Malaysian pharmacists and suppliers struggle to meet demand for masks|work=The Star/Asia News Network|via=The Straits Times|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315121409/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-malaysian-pharmacists-and-suppliers-struggle-to-meet-demand-for-masks|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the federal government has assured the supply of masks to be replenished with a total of 10 million masks to enter Malaysian markets in the nearest time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/21/saifuddin-10-million-face-masks-to-flood-malaysian-market-within-a-week/1839707|title=Saifuddin: 10 million face masks to flood Malaysian market within a week|agency=Bernama|work=The Malay Mail|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223033101/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/21/saifuddin-10-million-face-masks-to-flood-malaysian-market-within-a-week/1839707|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574098/face-masks-will-soon-be-replenished|title=Face masks will soon be replenished|last=Arumugam|first=Tharanya|work=New Straits Times|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315045637/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574098/face-masks-will-soon-be-replenished|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> With the rapid spread of the virus infections into several more states such as Penang and Sabah in the country,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/12/loo-and-behold-panic-buying-hits-penang|title=Loo and behold, panic buying hits Penang|work=The Star|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314022550/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/12/loo-and-behold-panic-buying-hits-penang|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-covid-19-case-announced|title=People starting to stock up goods in parts of Sabah after first Covid-19 case announced|last=Lee|first=Stephanie|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314022539/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/panic-buying-hits-sabah-after-first-covid-19-case-announced|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> panic buying has seen an increase nationwide with people began to packing excessive essential items.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575302/covid-19-panic-buying-supermarkets-nationwide|title=Covid-19: Panic buying at supermarkets nationwide|work=New Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317075041/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575302/covid-19-panic-buying-supermarkets-nationwide|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This causing some of the major [[supermarket]] operators in the country to continuously assured the public that there is adequate supply of essentials and urging most people to not engage in panic buying despite the recently announced move by the federal government to impose movement control within the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/supermarts-tell-malaysians-to-resist-panic-buying-as-country-shuts-down-for/1847330|title=Supermarts tell Malaysians to resist panic buying as country shuts down for Covid-19|last=Chalil|first=Melanie|work=The Malay Mail|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317080830/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/supermarts-tell-malaysians-to-resist-panic-buying-as-country-shuts-down-for/1847330|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal government also in the consideration to ban face masks exports as a result of the increasing mask shortages with the Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry to raise the increasing shortages issues of surgical masks and hand sanitisers to the [[Cabinet of Malaysia|Malaysian Cabinet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574635/government-considering-face-mask-export-ban|title=Government considering face mask export ban|work=Bernama|via=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315045953/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574635/government-considering-face-mask-export-ban|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574820/face-mask-hand-sanitiser-shortage-be-raised-cabinet-meeting|title=Face mask, hand sanitiser shortage to be raised at Cabinet meeting|work=Bernama|via=New Straits Times|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316105848/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574820/face-mask-hand-sanitiser-shortage-be-raised-cabinet-meeting|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 March, the enforcement to ban face masks export was gazetted under the Control of Supplies (Prohibition on Export) \u2013 (Amendment) Regulations 2020 covering four type of face masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/minister-bans-malaysia-from-exporting-face-masks/1847543|title=Minister bans Malaysia from exporting face masks|last=Lim|first=Ida|work=The Malay Mail|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319012034/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/17/minister-bans-malaysia-from-exporting-face-masks/1847543|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Apart from enacting law banning face masks exports to meet the struggling domestic public demands, the federal government announced that it will import 10 million face masks from China by stages to increase nationwide supply with the importation of face masks from other countries also being allowed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/govt-now-allows-import-of-face-masks-says-minister/|title=Govt now allows import of face masks, says minister|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321061547/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/govt-now-allows-import-of-face-masks-says-minister/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/minister-govt-to-import-10-million-face-masks-from-china/1848686|title=Minister: Govt to import 10 million face masks from China|last=Bunyan|first=John|work=The Malay Mail|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321061729/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/minister-govt-to-import-10-million-face-masks-from-china/1848686|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/govt-to-import-10-mil-face-masks-from-china/|title=Govt to import 10 mil face masks from China|last=Agustin|first=Robin|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321061340/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/govt-to-import-10-mil-face-masks-from-china/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Sporting and other events ===\nThe pandemic outbreak has forced the cancellations and postponements of many events in the country; including both local and international.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2020/03/571362/major-events-postponed-due-covid-19-outbreak|title=Major events postponed due to Covid-19 outbreak|last=Yusof|first=Ayisy|work=New Straits Times|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314002747/https://www.nst.com.my/business/2020/03/571362/major-events-postponed-due-covid-19-outbreak|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All sports and co-curricular activities in schools were postponed with immediate effects as announced by the country Ministry of Education.<ref name=\"sports and co-curricular activities in schools postponed\"/> Major Anglican and [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Catholic Masses]] in West Malaysia as well as in Sabah and Sarawak were also postponed,<ref>{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/12/covid-19-catholic-church-suspends-mass-for-two-weeks|title=Covid-19: Catholic Church suspends mass for two weeks|work=The Star|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314023641/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/12/covid-19-catholic-church-suspends-mass-for-two-weeks|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148682/suspension-of-catholic-masses-and-gatherings/|title=Suspension of Catholic Masses and gatherings|work=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314023506/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148682/suspension-of-catholic-masses-and-gatherings/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}<br />{{*}} {{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/14/covid-19-church-services-in-sarawak-brunei-suspended-temporarily/|title=Covid-19: Anglican church services in Sarawak, Brunei suspended temporarily|last=Edgar|first=Nigel|work=Borneo Post|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314023803/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/14/covid-19-church-services-in-sarawak-brunei-suspended-temporarily/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while annual cultural events in Sabah such as the [[Kaamatan]] ([[Kadazan-Dusun|Kadazan-Dusun festival]]) and Kalimaran ([[Murut people|Murut festival]]) have been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148676/kaamatan-festival-2020-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/|title=Kaamatan Festival 2020 cancelled due to Covid-19|work=Daily Express|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314021932/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148676/kaamatan-festival-2020-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/554452/dua-pesta-tahunan-sabah-dibatalkan|title=Dua pesta tahunan Sabah dibatalkan|trans-title=Two annual Sabah festivals are cancelled|last=Dahali|first=Rafiqah|language=Malay|work=Harian Metro|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315044826/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2020/03/554452/dua-pesta-tahunan-sabah-dibatalkan|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite Muslim [[Friday prayer|Friday sermon]] (except for the state of [[Perlis]] on 13 March)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysias-perlis-cancels-friday-prayers-amid-coronavirus-fears-other-states-continue|title=Malaysia's Perlis cancels Friday prayers amid coronavirus fears; other states continue|last=H. Rodzi|first=Nadirah|work=The Straits Times|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314073303/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysias-perlis-cancels-friday-prayers-amid-coronavirus-fears-other-states-continue|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> are still not suspended due to the virus, the Yang-di Pertuan Agong of Malaysia has called for shorter sermon and every mosques in the country must provide forehead [[thermometer]], hand sanitiser and face masks as part of the prevention measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/agong-calls-for-shorter-friday-sermon-mosques-to-take-preventative-measure/1846307|title=Agong calls for shorter Friday sermon, mosques to take preventative measures against Covid-19|work=Bernama|via=The Malay Mail|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314030555/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/13/agong-calls-for-shorter-friday-sermon-mosques-to-take-preventative-measure/1846307|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A guidelines on Friday sermon has been released by the [[Ministry of Religious Affairs|Religious Affairs Minister]] of Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://says.com/my/news/religious-affairs-minister-dr-zulkifli-issues-covid-19-guidelines-regarding-friday-prayers|title=Religious Affairs Minister Dr Zulkifli Issues COVID-19 Guidelines Regarding Friday Prayers|last=Ram|first=Sadho|work=Says.com|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> With the [[Malaysia national football team]] will play the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|2022 World Cup qualifiers]], the Malaysians planned to play a friendly game against [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] before facing the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]] and [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]. It was later announced that the friendly would not take part due to severe outbreak in Malaysia and, later, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bahrain|Bahrain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/1235332/international-friendly-between-malaysia-and-bahrain-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=International friendly between Malaysia and Bahrain cancelled due to coronavirus outbreak|work=Fox Sports Asia|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314031304/https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/1235332/international-friendly-between-malaysia-and-bahrain-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further sporting events such as golf's [[Maybank Championship]] and other local tournament were immediately called off while other sporting events such as badminton's [[Malaysia Open (badminton)|Malaysia Open]], football's [[M-League]], hockey's [[Azlan Shah Cup]], squash's [[Asian Squash Team Championships|Asian Team Championship]] and Malaysian Schools Sports Council events were either cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/sports/2020/03/13/malaysian-golf-association-cancels-all-tournaments-over-covid-19/1846143|title=Malaysian Golf Association cancels all tournaments over Covid-19|last=Palansamy|first=Yiswaree|work=The Malay Mail|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314061639/https://www.malaymail.com/news/sports/2020/03/13/malaysian-golf-association-cancels-all-tournaments-over-covid-19/1846143|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/sports/badminton/2020/03/574526/malaysia-open-cancelled|title=Malaysia Open cancelled|work=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314061838/https://www.nst.com.my/sports/badminton/2020/03/574526/malaysia-open-cancelled|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/sports/golf/2020/03/574498/malaysias-sports-casualties-coronavirus|title=Malaysia's sports casualties of coronavirus|last=Singh|first=Jugjet|work=New Straits Times|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314040010/https://www.nst.com.my/sports/golf/2020/03/574498/malaysias-sports-casualties-coronavirus|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Funds and aid on the pandemic ==\n=== Exchange of aid between China and Malaysia ===\n==== January\u2013February aid to China ====\nMalaysian aid organisation {{gray|#OpsHarapan}} aimed to collect 10,000 [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 face masks]] for its relief efforts to Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/31/opsharapan-targets-up-to-10000-face-masks-supplies-for-wuhan-aid/1833201|title=#OpsHarapan targets up to 10,000 face masks, supplies for Wuhan aid|last=Annuar|first=Azril|work=The Malay Mail|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226054230/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/31/opsharapan-targets-up-to-10000-face-masks-supplies-for-wuhan-aid/1833201|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A total of 18 million pieces of [[medical glove]]s were donated by Malaysia to assist China in their struggle against the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/01/31/coronavirus-malaysia-to-donate-18-million-medical-gloves-to-china|title=Coronavirus: Malaysia to donate 18 million medical gloves to China|last=Kaos Jr|first=Joseph|work=The Star|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/31/malaysian-rubber-export-promotion-council-others-to-donate-18-million-glove/1833228|title=Malaysian Rubber Export Promotion Council, others to donate 18 million medical gloves to Wuhan|last=Palansamy|first=Yiswaree|work=The Malay Mail|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223093203/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/01/31/malaysian-rubber-export-promotion-council-others-to-donate-18-million-glove/1833228|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/10/hit-by-ncov-asian-business-group-to-truck-three-million-malaysian-medical-g/1836011|title=Hit by nCoV, Asian business group to truck three million Malaysian medical gloves to Wuhan|last=Bunyan|first=John|work=The Malay Mail|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223093036/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/10/hit-by-ncov-asian-business-group-to-truck-three-million-malaysian-medical-g/1836011|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Malaysia's state [[Government of Sabah]] has raised RM2&nbsp;million for the \"Wuhan Fund\" which will be channelled to China as a sign of solidarity with the country during the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/02/20/sabah-govt-raised-rm2-million-for-wuhan-fund/|title=Sabah govt raised RM2&nbsp;million for Wuhan fund|agency=Bernama|work=Borneo Post|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223090803/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/02/20/sabah-govt-raised-rm2-million-for-wuhan-fund/|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state government fund's earlier target was RM1&nbsp;million although the amount received exceeded the initial target when a local [[philanthropist]] contributed RM40,000 (US$9,548).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/565555/philanthropist-contributes-rm40000-sabahs-wuhan-fund|title=Philanthropist contributes RM40,000 to Sabah's Wuhan Fund|last=Geraldine|first=Avila|work=New Straits Times|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223091344/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/565555/philanthropist-contributes-rm40000-sabahs-wuhan-fund|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/566469/sabahs-wuhan-fund-exceeds-rm1-million-target|title=Sabah's Wuhan Fund exceeds RM1&nbsp;million target|last=Miwil|first=Olivia|work=New Straits Times|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223091541/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/566469/sabahs-wuhan-fund-exceeds-rm1-million-target|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The fundraising was organised in a joint event called \"We Love, We Care\" by the Sabah government and Chinese associations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/19/c_138797438.htm|title=Malaysia's Sabah state host charity event for China's fight against COVID-19|agency=Xinhua News Agency|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228124458/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/19/c_138797438.htm|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A group of musicians in Malaysia also published a song to support China in their struggle against the virus titled \"You Are Not Alone\" which was featured in a show in Malaysia's capital of Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/17/c_138792313.htm|title=Xinhua Headlines: \"You are not alone\" -- countries worldwide offer support, aid to China's fight against coronavirus|last1=Liena|first1=Fei|last2=Ran|first2=Dan|agency=Xinhua News Agency|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March\u2013April aid to Malaysia ====\nFollowing the Malaysian government's move to impose the Movement Control Order as a late-stage containment, the [[Government of China|Chinese government]] through its ambassador in Malaysia has stated that they are committed to aid by supplying [[disinfectant]]s, face masks, [[COVID-19 testing#PCR|PCR testing kits]], sanitisers and [[ventilator]]s to help the latter contain the further spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/hishammuddin-chinese-government-will-be-supplying-masks-and-disinfectants-to-malaysia/|title=Hishammuddin: Chinese Government Will Be Supplying Masks And Disinfectants To Malaysia|last=Velusamy|first=Thermesh|work=World of Buzz|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317083214/https://www.worldofbuzz.com/hishammuddin-chinese-government-will-be-supplying-masks-and-disinfectants-to-malaysia/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sea.mashable.com/culture/9609/china-will-send-medical-aid-to-malaysia-amidst-the-countrys-movement-control-order|title=China will send medical aid to Malaysia amidst the country's movement control order|last=Gill|first=Tarvin|work=Mashable Southeast Asia|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318020945/https://sea.mashable.com/culture/9609/china-will-send-medical-aid-to-malaysia-amidst-the-countrys-movement-control-order|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first medical supplies were sent to [[Sungai Buloh Hospital]] on 19 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chinapress.com.my/20200319/%e2%97%a4%e5%85%a8%e7%90%83%e5%a4%a7%e6%b5%81%e8%a1%8c%e2%97%a2%e4%b8%ad%e5%9b%bd%e9%a6%96%e6%89%b9%e6%8d%90%e8%b5%a0%e7%89%a9%e8%b5%84-%e9%80%81%e5%be%80%e5%8f%8c%e6%ba%aa%e6%af%9b%e7%b3%af%e5%8c%bb/|title=\u25e4\u6b66\u6c49\u80ba\u708e\u00b7\u5927\u9a6c\u9996\u5b97\u4eba\u4f20\u4eba\u25e2-\u786e\u8bca\u518d\u6dfb2\u4eba 1\u60a3\u8005\u662f\u9996\u540d\u786e\u8bca\u75c5\u60a3\u59b9|trans-title=\u25e4Global pandemic\u25e2China's first batch of donated materials sent to Sungai Buloh Hospital|language=Chinese|work=China Press|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319044424/https://www.chinapress.com.my/20200319/%e2%97%a4%e5%85%a8%e7%90%83%e5%a4%a7%e6%b5%81%e8%a1%8c%e2%97%a2%e4%b8%ad%e5%9b%bd%e9%a6%96%e6%89%b9%e6%8d%90%e8%b5%a0%e7%89%a9%e8%b5%84-%e9%80%81%e5%be%80%e5%8f%8c%e6%ba%aa%e6%af%9b%e7%b3%af%e5%8c%bb/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further 100,000 face masks were sent by the President of China-Asia Economic Development Association to Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/20/100k-face-masks-arriving-from-china-on-march-20|title=100k face masks arriving from China on March 20|last=Lai|first=Allison|work=The Star|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131944/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/20/100k-face-masks-arriving-from-china-on-march-20|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Along the same day, Chinese [[Alibaba Group]] founder [[Jack Ma]] further announced that through his foundation, a total of 2 million masks, 150,000 test kits, 20,000 [[personal protective equipment|protective suit]]s and 20,000 [[face shield]]s will be sent to four Southeast Asian countries including Malaysia to aid these nations in their struggle against the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200319005410/en/|title=Jack Ma Foundation and Alibaba Foundation Announce Donations to Four Southeast Asian Countries|work=Business Wire|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320022235/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200319005410/en/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further total of 1,000 face masks, 20,000 medical masks, 100 [[personal protective equipment|protective clothing]] and 100 [[goggle]]s were contributed by China specifically for the Malaysian police forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/malaysia-receives-medical-devices-from-china-for-police/|title=Malaysia receives medical devices from China for police|work=Free Malaysia Today|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321055741/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/malaysia-receives-medical-devices-from-china-for-police/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> China's Consulate-General in Kota Kinabalu also has announced that medical aid to be dispatched to Sabah to aid their struggle against the virus and reciprocate the people's of Sabah recent assistance to Mainland China during the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149233/china-to-send-medical-aid-to-sabah/|title=EXCLUSIVE: China to send medical aid to Sabah|work=Daily Express|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321070223/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149233/china-to-send-medical-aid-to-sabah/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/china-to-reciprocate-sabahs-kindness-liang/|title=China to reciprocate Sabah's kindness \u2013 Liang|work=Borneo Post|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324032130/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/china-to-reciprocate-sabahs-kindness-liang/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March, a further total of 5,500 test kits were delivered to Malaysia's Health Ministry by China through its several business entities operating in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/25/china-donates-5500-covid-19-test-kits-to-malaysia-on-top-of-previous-donati/1850148|title=China donates 5,500 Covid-19 test kits to Malaysia, on top of previous donations of face masks|last=Lim|first=Ida|work=The Malay Mail|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405150649/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/25/china-donates-5500-covid-19-test-kits-to-malaysia-on-top-of-previous-donati/1850148|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, 20,000 N95 face masks were delivered by China for the Malaysia's state of Sarawak Frontline healthcare workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/26/covid-19-sarawak-receives-20000-face-masks-from-china039s-fujian-province|title=Covid-19: Sarawak receives 20,000 face masks from China's Fujian province|work=The Star|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405162820/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/26/covid-19-sarawak-receives-20000-face-masks-from-china039s-fujian-province|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 29 March, China delivered a total of 83 boxes of face masks with 2,000 pieces to Malaysia's state of Sabah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/29/sabah-gets-fresh-boost-of-medical-masks-supplies-from-china/1851448|title=Sabah gets fresh boost of medical masks, supplies from China|last=Chan|first=Julia|work=The Malay Mail|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405151732/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/29/sabah-gets-fresh-boost-of-medical-masks-supplies-from-china/1851448|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further 170,000 boxes of face masks, 1,000 sets of personal protective equipment (PPE), 200 pairs of goggles, hand sanitisers and surgical masks were delivered by China to the Sabah state government on 30 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149813/china-sends-masks-and-sanitisers/|title=China sends masks and sanitisers|last=Ralon|first=Larry|work=Daily Express|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405160213/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149813/china-sends-masks-and-sanitisers/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another 20,000 surgical masks destined for Sabah's healthcare frontliner workers were delivered in early April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/region/news.php?id=1828245|title=Sabah receives additional 20,000 surgical masks from China|agency=Bernama|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> A total of 30,000 face masks were delivered by China through its Consulate General in Kuching specifically for the Sarawak State Disaster Management Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/01/chinas-consulate-general-donates-30000-face-masks-to-sarawak/|title=China\u2019s Consulate General donates 30,000 face masks to Sarawak|work=Borneo Post|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405162003/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/01/chinas-consulate-general-donates-30000-face-masks-to-sarawak/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Aid from other countries ===\nThe Malaysian government was also given aid from the [[United Arab Emirates]], which included 600,000 face masks, 200 ventilators, about 100,000 test kits and 50,000 protective clothings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/malaysia-terima-peralatan-perubatan-dari-uae-235962|title=Malaysia terima peralatan perubatan dari UAE|trans-title=Malaysia received medical equipments from UAE|last=Rahman|first=Abdul Hakim|language=Malay|work=Astro Awani|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405143723/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/malaysia-terima-peralatan-perubatan-dari-uae-235962|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Neighbouring [[Singapore]] had donated 5,000 universal transport medium (UTM) swabs, a critical component in test kits which can test for a case of the virus within minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2020/04/singapore-donate-utm-swabs-malaysia/|title=S'pore donates 5,000 UTM swabs to M'sia for Covid-19 test kits|last=Said|first=Sulaiman|work=Mothership.sg|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405145009/https://mothership.sg/2020/04/singapore-donate-utm-swabs-malaysia/|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Local pandemic fund within Malaysia ===\nFollowing the severely strained healthcare system due to the increasing number of infections by the virus, [[Mercy Malaysia]] launched the \"Covid-19 Pandemic Fund\" to supporting medical services and the essential needs of marginalised groups within the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/mercy-malaysia-launches-covid-19-fund-BA2147388|title=Mercy Malaysia launches Covid-19 fund|work=Bernama|via=The Sun|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319015610/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/mercy-malaysia-launches-covid-19-fund-BA2147388|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Malaysian Red Crescent Society]] also launched the #responsMALAYSIA (Malaysia's Response) initiative to support frontliners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/577648/red-crescent-leads-way-covid-19-battle|title=Red Crescent leads way in COVID-19 battle|work=New Straits Times|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405143007/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/577648/red-crescent-leads-way-covid-19-battle|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVarious Malaysian states have launched their own stimulus packages and announced immediate financial aid in the form of rental waivers and deferment of student loan repayments to help their citizens to cope throughout the virus outbreak with the federal government of Malaysia also announced it will disburse a total of RM130 million equally among Malaysia's 13 states to help small traders, the infected victims and front-line staff including those in the healthcare sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-malaysian-states-begin-to-hand-out-aid-for-those-affected-by-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: Malaysian states begin handing out aid to those affected by outbreak|last=Hassan|first=Hazlin|work=The Straits Times|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325030414/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-malaysian-states-begin-to-hand-out-aid-for-those-affected-by-outbreak|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February, Malaysia's home improvement retailer MR DIY distributed a total of 3.5 million free face masks nationwide to help curb the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/06/mr-diy-hands-out-35-million-masks-free-to-combat-virus|title=MR DIY hands out 3.5 million masks free to combat virus|work=Bernama|via=The Star|date=6 February 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325022819/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/06/mr-diy-hands-out-35-million-masks-free-to-combat-virus|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Further in March, Coway Malaysia donated a total of 100,000 pieces of surgical face masks to PDRM in an effort to help safeguard police personnel who are on the frontlines during the global pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/24/coway-malaysia-donates-thousands-of-protective-face-masks-to-pdrm|title=Coway Malaysia donates thousands of protective face masks to PDRM|work=The Star|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325022419/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/24/coway-malaysia-donates-thousands-of-protective-face-masks-to-pdrm|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVarious Malaysian banks such as [[Affin Bank]], [[Agrobank]], [[Alliance Bank Malaysia Berhad|Alliance Bank]], [[AmBank]], [[Bank Islam Malaysia]], [[Bank Muamalat Malaysia]], [[Bank Rakyat]], [[Bank Simpanan Nasional]], [[CIMB]], [[Hong Leong Bank]], [[HSBC Bank Malaysia]], [[Maybank]], MBSB Bank, [[OCBC Bank]], [[Public Bank Berhad]], [[RHB Bank]] and [[SME Bank]] has offered measures including financial assistance for its customers amidst the virus crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2020/03/20/banks-step-up-measures-to-help-customers-amidst-covid-19-crisis|title=Banks step up measures to help customers amidst Covid-19 crisis|work=The Star|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ringgitplus.com/en/blog/bank-news/malaysian-banks-offer-deferment-of-loan-repayments-for-customers-affected-by-wuhan-coronavirus.html|title=Malaysian Banks And Local Institutions Offer Financial Assistance For Customers Affected By Covid-19|last=Cheong|first=Alex|work=RinggitPlus|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325023543/https://ringgitplus.com/en/blog/bank-news/malaysian-banks-offer-deferment-of-loan-repayments-for-customers-affected-by-wuhan-coronavirus.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Local broadcasting and telecommunications companies aid ====\nTo keep the Malaysian public entertained during the movement control order period, both Malaysia's [[pay television]] and internet services of [[Unifi (internet service provider)|Unifi]] offers free access to all Unifi TV channels while its mobile prepaid of Unifi Mobile offers unlimited data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soyacincau.com/2020/03/18/tm-unifi-free-access-all-unifi-tv-channels/|title=Unifi offers free access to all Unifi TV channels|last=Wong|first=Alexander|work=SoyaCincau|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326011734/https://www.soyacincau.com/2020/03/18/tm-unifi-free-access-all-unifi-tv-channels/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vernonchan.com/unifi-mobile-free-unlimited-data-movement-control-order/|title=Unifi Mobile offers free unlimited data during Movement Control Order|author=Vernon|work=VernonChan|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326011925/https://vernonchan.com/unifi-mobile-free-unlimited-data-movement-control-order/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Astro (television)|Astro]] also offers free access to all of its paid movie channels through both basic Astro and Astro GO mobile application.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soyacincau.com/2020/03/17/astro-offers-free-access-to-all-movie-channels-starting-18-march/|title=Astro offers free access to all movie channels starting 18 March|last=Wong|first=Alexander|work=SoyaCincau|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326012311/https://www.soyacincau.com/2020/03/17/astro-offers-free-access-to-all-movie-channels-starting-18-march/|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Government relief assistance ====\nOn 27 March, Prime Minister [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] launched the federal government's RM250 billion Prihatin stimulus package to help people, businesses and the economy to weather the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/business/pm-announces-rm250b-stimulus-package-GN2186787|title=PM announces RM250b stimulus package|work=Bernama|via=The Sun|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405081249/https://www.thesundaily.my/business/pm-announces-rm250b-stimulus-package-GN2186787|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Prihatin stimulus package consists of RM128 billion for welfare assistance, RM100 billion to support small and medium businesses, RM2 billion to strengthen the country's economy, and a RM20 billion stimulus package that was previously announced by the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/stimulus-package-rm1600-to-almost-4-million-household-with-income-of-rm4000-and-below-BN2186829|title=Stimulus package: RM1,600 to almost 4 million household with income of RM4,000 and below|last=Loo|first=Cindi|work=The Sun|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405082018/https://www.thesundaily.my/local/updated-stimulus-package-rm1600-to-almost-4-million-household-with-income-of-rm4000-and-below-BN2186829|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The regional economist Brian Tan from [[Barclays]], said that the central bank would cut interest rates to 1%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/kl-needs-to-flood-market-with-liquidity-say-analysts|title=KL needs to flood market with liquidity, say analysts|last=Teoh|first=Shannon|work=The Straits Times|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405082532/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/kl-needs-to-flood-market-with-liquidity-say-analysts|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nFollowing the [[Tablighi Jamaat]] gathering at a [[Sri Petaling]] mosque, it had since then been identified as a vector point for the Covid-19 virus. The Malaysian Government, under [[2020 Malaysian political crisis|political turmoil]], and authorities were criticised for not doing anything to prevent the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575560/how-sri-petaling-tabligh-became-southeast-asias-covid-19-hotspot|title=How Sri Petaling tabligh became Southeast Asia's Covid-19 hotspot|work=New Straits Times|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326004049/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575560/how-sri-petaling-tabligh-became-southeast-asias-covid-19-hotspot|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy related to insufficient facemasks and pricing ===\n{{empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Controversy related to quarantine regulations in University of Malaya ===\nStudent volunteers at [[University of Malaya]] claim they are designed to deal with the \"quarantine\" of students returning from China in the new semester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/16/volunteers-we-were-told-to-manage-china-students|title=Volunteers: We were told to manage China students|last=Rajaendram|first=Rebecca|work=The Star|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405163552/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/16/volunteers-we-were-told-to-manage-china-students|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/features/coronavirus-affected-countries-malaysia-covid-19-outbreak-measures-tourism-economy-impact/|title=Coronavirus in Malaysia: Covid-19 outbreak, measures and impact|last=Duddu|first=Praveen|work=Pharmaceutical Technology|year=2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/08/can-malaysia-handle-the-corona-virus/1835667|title=Can Malaysia handle the corona virus? The five times when we dealt with health emergencies|work=SoyaCincau|via=The Malay Mail|date=8 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228190040/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/08/can-malaysia-handle-the-corona-virus/1835667|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/19/malaysia-prepare-for-the-war-effort-against-covid-19/1848100|title=Malaysia, prepare for the 'war effort' against Covid-19|last=Chin Tong|first=Liew|work=The Malay Mail|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web